  ('prep-hash-maps-find-top-k-tweet-words-in-last::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-find-top-k-tweet-words-in-last', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Tweet  ("", t=) sits inside  … , so it counts. counts[""] = .', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'Which approach fits "Find X to make array sum to K"?', 'Cap each value at x; cappedSum rises monotonically with x', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::init', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'At the start of a run (Find X to make array sum to K), what strategy is established?', 'Find the smallest cap x so that capping every value at x makes the array sum reach . cappedSum(a, x) only ever grows as x grows, so we can binary-search x. First sort the array: [].', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'On the "TEST" step (cap()=>=), what happens?', 'Test mid = : cappedSum =  which is at least . This x works, but a smaller one might too — keep it as a candidate by setting hi = mid.', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::state', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'What does the `a` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `a` in sync: sorted array', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find X to make array sum to K"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). binary-search x on cappedSum(a,x) >= target', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-find-x-to-make-array-sum-to-k', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'lo and hi have met at x = . cappedSum(a, ) =  ≥ , and no smaller cap reaches . The answer is .', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'Which approach fits "Find year with most population"?', '+1 at birth, -1 at death+1; sweep years tracking running population', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::init', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'At the start of a run (Find year with most population), what strategy is established?', 'Find the year with the most people alive. Each person spans [birth, death]. Instead of touching every year of every life, we record only the changes: +1 the year someone is born, −1 the year after they die. Then a single sweep of the change points gives the running population.', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'On the "SORT" step ( change years), what happens?', 'The delta map is complete. Collect its keys and sort them: []. These are the only years where the population can change, so we sweep them left to right with a prefix sum.', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::state', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'What does the `intervals` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `intervals` in sync: the raw input intervals', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find year with most population"?', 'O(p log p). O(y). delta[birth]++, delta[death+1]--; prefix-sum, track peak year', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-find-year-with-most-population', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The sweep is finished. The maximum running population was , first reached in year . Return .', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'Which approach fits "Get all element counts"?', 'Tally every value into a count map', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::init', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'At the start of a run (Get all element counts), what strategy is established?', 'Get all element counts: walk the array once and tally every value into a hash map. counts[x]++ builds a frequency map of how many times each value appears. Time O(n), Space O(n).', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'On the "BUMP" step (counts[]=), what happens?', 'counts[] is now . The map remembers every distinct value and how often it has appeared so far.', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::state', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being tallied', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Get all element counts"?', 'O(n). O(n). counts[x]++', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-get-all-element-counts', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The whole array is tallied. The frequency map holds  distinct value with their counts — that is the answer.', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'Which approach fits "Object as key"?', 'The whole struct value is the map key; Go compares its fields', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::init', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'At the start of a run (Object as key), what strategy is established?', 'Object as key: the grades map is keyed by the whole Student struct, so a lookup matches only when BOTH ID and Name are equal. We scan the students list and copy each one that exists in the map into the result.', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'On the "COPY" step (result[]=), what happens?', 'Hit — the struct key {,""} is present with grade . Copy it into the result: result[{,""}] = .', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::state', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: index of the student currently being looked up', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Object as key"?', 'O(1) per op. O(n). map[Student]; copy grades[s] when present', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-object-as-key::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-object-as-key', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Done.  of  students were found in the grades map and copied to the result. Each lookup was O(1); the result holds O(n) entries.', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'Which approach fits "Remove duplicate contacts"?', 'Any shared email unions two contacts into one group', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::init', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'At the start of a run (Remove duplicate contacts), what strategy is established?', 'Remove duplicate contacts: two contacts are the same person if they share any email. We use union-find — each contact starts as its own group, and any shared email unions two groups into one.', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'On the "OWN_EMAIL" step ( → id ), what happens?', 'Email "" is new, so contact # claims it: emailOwner[""] = .', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::state', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'What does the `ids` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `ids` in sync: contact ids in input order (the ArrayRow cells)', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Remove duplicate contacts"?', 'O(n·e·α(n)). O(n·e). emailOwner seen -> union; else claim; emit one per root', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-remove-duplicate-contacts', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Done.  input contacts collapse to  unique : ${roots.map((r) => ', 5),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::pattern', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'Which approach fits "Sort pairs"?', 'key->next chain; the head is the key that is never a value', 0),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::init', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'At the start of a run (Sort pairs), what strategy is established?', 'Sort pairs: each entry links a key to its next value. We rebuild the single chain by finding the head (a key that never appears as a value) and walking the map from there.', 1),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::key-step', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'On the "SCAN" step ( in dest), what happens?', '"" is also a destination, so something points to it — it is not the head. Keep looking.', 2),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::state', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'What does the `pairs` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `pairs` in sync: the raw key->next links', 3),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::complexity', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Sort pairs"?', 'O(n). O(n). find start not in dest; walk the map building ''a-b''', 4),
  ('prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs::outcome', 'prep-hash-maps-sort-pairs', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Done. The reconstructed route is [] — one pass to find destinations, one to find the head, one to walk the chain: Time O(n), Space O(n).', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::pattern', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'Which approach fits "Count intervals range"?', 'Merge touching intervals; sum each merged group''s span', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::init', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'At the start of a run (Count intervals range), what strategy is established?', 'Count Intervals Range: total number of distinct integers covered by the union of these intervals. Sort by start, then sweep left to right merging intervals that touch or overlap (start ≤ end+1), adding end−start+1 for each merged group.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::key-step', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'On the "STOP" step (gap before ), what happens?', ' starts at  > end+1 (+1), leaving a gap. The current group [,] is complete.', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::state', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'What does the `sorted` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `sorted` in sync: intervals after sorting by start', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::complexity', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Count intervals range"?', 'O(n log n). O(1). sort by start; extend while start<=end+1; add end-start+1', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-count-intervals-range::outcome', 'prep-intervals-count-intervals-range', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Swept all intervals. The merged groups ${merged.map((m) => ', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::pattern', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'Which approach fits "Distance of nearest stores"?', 'For each customer, the minimum squared distance to any store', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::init', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'At the start of a run (Distance of nearest stores), what strategy is established?', 'Distance of nearest stores: for every customer we brute-force the squared Euclidean distance (dx²+dy²) to each of the  stores and keep the smallest. No square roots are taken — comparing squared distances preserves the ordering. Time O(s·c), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::key-step', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'On the "KEEP" step (d= ≥ ), what happens?', 'Store   gives distance² = , which is not closer than the current best (). Keep best unchanged.', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::state', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'What does the `ci` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `ci` in sync: index of customer currently being processed', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::complexity', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Distance of nearest stores"?', 'O(s * c). O(1). brute force dx^2+dy^2; keep the min per customer', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores::outcome', 'prep-intervals-distance-of-nearest-stores', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every customer is resolved. The result array of nearest squared distances is [].', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::pattern', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'Which approach fits "Draw skyline"?', 'Sweep x events; keep a multiset of active heights; emit when the max changes', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::init', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'At the start of a run (Draw skyline), what strategy is established?', 'Draw Skyline (sweep line): each building [L,R,h] becomes two x-events — a start (encoded as −h) and an end (encoded as +h). Sorting by (x, signedHeight) makes starts win ties so a taller building opens before a shorter one closes. We keep a multiset of active heights {0:1} and emit a key-point whenever the tallest active height changes.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::key-step', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'On the "EMIT" step ((,)), what happens?', 'The tallest active height changed from  to , so the skyline turns here: emit key-point (, ). This marks where the visible roofline steps up or down.', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::state', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'What does the `cur` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cur` in sync: index of the event being processed', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::complexity', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Draw skyline"?', 'O(n^2). O(n). start=-h, end=+h; sort by (x,height); track height counts; record max changes', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-draw-skyline::outcome', 'prep-intervals-draw-skyline', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All events processed. The skyline is the  emitted key-points: ${result.map((p) => ', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::pattern', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'Which approach fits "Insert interval"?', 'Before / overlap-merge / after segments around the new interval', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::init', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'At the start of a run (Insert interval), what strategy is established?', 'Insert Interval: the existing intervals  are sorted and non-overlapping. We splice in  using three segments — copy everything strictly before it, absorb every overlap into x, then copy everything after.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::key-step', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'On the "PLACE" step (place ), what happens?', 'No more overlaps. The fully merged interval  now goes into the result at position .', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::state', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'What does the `x` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `x` in sync: the new interval as it grows by absorbing overlaps', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::complexity', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Insert interval"?', 'O(n). O(n). copy before; absorb overlaps into x; copy the rest', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-insert-interval::outcome', 'prep-intervals-insert-interval', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Done. The result  stays sorted and non-overlapping. Time O(n), space O(n) for the output list.', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-is-overlapped::pattern', 'prep-intervals-is-overlapped', 'Which approach fits "Is overlapped"?', 'Overlap iff both the x-ranges and the y-ranges intersect with positive area', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-is-overlapped::key-step', 'prep-intervals-is-overlapped', 'On the "EDGES_Y" step (max(,)=), what happens?', 'Rightmost bottom edge: max(, ) = . Any shared Y range must start here.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-is-overlapped::state', 'prep-intervals-is-overlapped', 'What does the `axis` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `axis` in sync: axis currently under inspection', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-is-overlapped::complexity', 'prep-intervals-is-overlapped', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is overlapped"?', 'O(1). O(1). min(rights) > max(lefts) on both X and Y', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-is-overlapped::outcome', 'prep-intervals-is-overlapped', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Lowest top edge: min(, ) = . Any shared Y range must end here.', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-is-square::pattern', 'prep-intervals-is-square', 'Which approach fits "Is square"?', 'A square has 4 equal sides, 2 equal diagonals, and side != diagonal', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-is-square::key-step', 'prep-intervals-is-square', 'On the "CHECK" step (counts[]=), what happens?', 'Check 1 — sides: d1 =  must occur exactly 4 times (the four edges). It occurs  time(s), so this check is .', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-is-square::state', 'prep-intervals-is-square', 'What does the `dists` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `dists` in sync: the 6 pairwise squared distances computed so far', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-is-square::complexity', 'prep-intervals-is-square', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is square"?', 'O(1). O(1). 6 pairwise dists; counts[side]==4 && counts[diag]==2 && side!=diag', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-is-square::outcome', 'prep-intervals-is-square', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Check 3 — distinctness: the side d1 =  and diagonal d2 =  must differ; otherwise the shape is degenerate. They are , so this check is .', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::pattern', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'Which approach fits "Meeting Rooms II"?', 'Separate starts and ends, sort each independently', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::init', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'At the start of a run (Meeting Rooms II), what strategy is established?', 'Meeting Rooms II: find the maximum number of meetings overlapping at any instant — that is how many rooms we need. We split every interval into its start time and its end time and treat the two as independent sorted timelines.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::key-step', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'On the "NEED" step (rooms=), what happens?', 'Meeting starting at  begins before the earliest end  ( < ), so no room has freed up yet — allocate a new room. rooms = .', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::state', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current start being processed', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::complexity', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Meeting Rooms II"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). Separate starts and ends, sort each independently; Sweep through starts: if `starts[i] < ends[endIdx]`, a new room is needed; else reuse a room (`endIdx++`)', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii::outcome', 'prep-intervals-meeting-rooms-ii', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every start has been swept. The most rooms held simultaneously was , so the answer is  meeting room.', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-merge-intervals::pattern', 'prep-intervals-merge-intervals', 'Which approach fits "Merge Intervals"?', 'Sort by start time, then greedily merge: if `curr[0] <= last[1]`, extend `last[1] = max(last[1], curr[1])`', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-merge-intervals::key-step', 'prep-intervals-merge-intervals', 'On the "EXTEND" step (), what happens?', ' overlaps the open interval because its start  ≤ open end . Its end  reaches further, so extend the open interval''s right edge to  → .', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-merge-intervals::state', 'prep-intervals-merge-intervals', 'What does the `sorted` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `sorted` in sync: intervals after sort by start', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-merge-intervals::complexity', 'prep-intervals-merge-intervals', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Merge Intervals"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). Sort by start time, then greedily merge: if `curr[0] <= last[1]`, extend `last[1] = max(last[1], curr[1])`; Otherwise, start a new interval', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-merge-intervals::outcome', 'prep-intervals-merge-intervals', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Sweep complete. The overlapping intervals collapsed into  disjoint interval: .', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::pattern', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'Which approach fits "Schedule meetings"?', 'Sort by start; any meeting starting before the previous end conflicts', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::init', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'At the start of a run (Schedule meetings), what strategy is established?', 'Schedule meetings: can one person attend every meeting? They can if and only if no two intervals overlap. Strategy — sort by start time, then check each meeting against the one before it.', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::key-step', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'On the "CONFLICT" step ( < ), what happens?', 'Overlap found:  starts at , which is before  ends at . The two meetings collide, so not all meetings can be attended — return false.', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::state', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'What does the `sorted` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `sorted` in sync: have we committed to the sorted order yet', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::complexity', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Schedule meetings"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). sort by start; sorted[i].Start < sorted[i-1].End -> false', 4),
  ('prep-intervals-schedule-meetings::outcome', 'prep-intervals-schedule-meetings', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'No overlap:  starts at , at or after  ends at . These two are compatible — keep sweeping.', 5),
  ('prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler::pattern', 'prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler', 'Which approach fits "Weighted job scheduler"?', 'Sort by end; dp = max(skip, take + best earlier non-overlapping job)', 0),
  ('prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler::key-step', 'prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler', 'On the "TAKE" step (take=), what happens?', 'Latest non-overlapping job is  (ends  ≤ ). Taking job  yields its profit  + dp[] (=) = .', 1),
  ('prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler::state', 'prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler', 'What does the `jobs` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `jobs` in sync: sorted by end time', 2),
  ('prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler::complexity', 'prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Weighted job scheduler"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). sort by end; dp[i]=max(dp[i-1], profit+dp[lastNonOverlap])', 3),
  ('prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler::outcome', 'prep-intervals-weighted-job-scheduler', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The table is complete. dp[] =  is the maximum total profit from any set of non-overlapping jobs.', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'Which approach fits "Add two numbers"?', 'Add the digit lists position by position with a carry', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::init', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'At the start of a run (Add two numbers), what strategy is established?', 'Add Two Numbers: each list stores a number''s digits least-significant first, so position 0 is the ones place. Walk both chains together, adding digit by digit and carrying overflow — exactly how you add by hand. Time O(max(n,m)), Space O(1) extra.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'On the "WRITE" step (node , carry ), what happens?', 'Write sum % 10 =  as the new node at position , and carry =  / 10 =  into the next position.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::state', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'What does the `pos` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `pos` in sync: current digit position being added', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Add two numbers"?', 'O(max(n,m)). O(1). sum=carry+l1+l2; node sum%10; carry=sum/10', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-add-two-numbers', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Both chains are exhausted and the carry is 0, so the result is complete. Reading the digits low-to-high gives the chain [].', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'Which approach fits "Copy List with Random Pointer"?', '**Interweave** technique (O(1) space, no hashmap): insert cloned node right after each original', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::init', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'At the start of a run (Copy List with Random Pointer), what strategy is established?', 'Copy List with Random Pointer using the Interweave trick (O(1) extra space, no hash map). Each clone is woven in right after its original so we can find it in place. The chain below already shows clones (lighter cells) sitting after each original.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'On the "RANDOM" step (clone→), what happens?', 'Original .Random points at original  (slot ). Its clone must point at the COPY of , which is the next slot (). Set clone.Random = original.Random.Next.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::state', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'What does the `cur` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cur` in sync: current slot under inspection', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Copy List with Random Pointer"?', 'O(n). O(1). **Interweave** technique (O(1) space, no hashmap): insert cloned node right after each original; Pass 2: set `curr.Next.Random = curr.Random.Next` (clone''s rand', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-copy-list-with-random-pointer', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Done — the deep copy [] is fully detached with its own Next and Random pointers, all in O(n) time and O(1) extra space.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'Which approach fits "Deep copy random pointers"?', 'Map original->clone; recurse Next and Random off the cache', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::init', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'At the start of a run (Deep copy random pointers), what strategy is established?', 'Deep copy a linked list whose nodes carry an extra Random pointer. We walk the structure recursively and keep a cache seen[original] = clone, so every original node is built exactly once and both its Next and Random links can point at the right clones. Time O(n), space O(n).', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'On the "CLONE" step (clone ), what happens?', 'First time we reach . Allocate a fresh clone with the same value () and store seen[] = clone right away, before recursing — caching up front is what makes the Random pointers safe.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::state', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'What does the `vals` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `vals` in sync: original node values, in chain order — the visible array', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Deep copy random pointers"?', 'O(n). O(n). seen[n] returns cached; clone Next and Random recursively', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-deep-copy-random-pointers', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every reachable node has been cloned once and both its Next and Random links rewired to point at clones — the cache holds  entries. The deep copy is complete and fully independent of the original.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'Which approach fits "Delete every Kth node in DLL"?', 'Walk counting; every kth node gets unlinked on both sides', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::init', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'At the start of a run (Delete every Kth node in DLL), what strategy is established?', 'Delete every Kth node in a doubly linked list. We walk left→right with a step counter; each time step reaches k we unlink that node on BOTH sides (prev.next = next, next.prev = prev) and reset the counter. Time O(n), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'On the "DELETE" step (unlink ), what happens?', 'Unlink node : set prev.next = next and next.prev = prev so it is bypassed on both sides of the DLL. Reset step to 0 and continue from the next node.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::state', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'What does the `k` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `k` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Delete every Kth node in DLL"?', 'O(n). O(1). step==k -> prev.Next=next, next.Prev=prev, reset step', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-every-kth-node-in-dll', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Node  (value ) is kept — it is only # since the last reset (need ). Advance the cursor.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'Which approach fits "Delete node"?', 'Steal the next node''s value, then skip over it', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::init', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'At the start of a run (Delete node), what strategy is established?', 'We are handed only a pointer to the node at index  (value ) — we cannot see the head or the previous node. The trick: copy the next node''s value over this one, then unlink the next node.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'On the "COPY" step (node.Val = ), what happens?', 'Steal the successor''s value: node.Val = node.Next.Val, so the node at index  now holds . The original value  is gone, but a duplicate of  now sits at two places.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::state', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'What does the `chain` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `chain` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Delete node"?', 'O(1). O(1). node.Val=next.Val; node.Next=next.Next', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-delete-node::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-delete-node', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Now relink past the successor: node.Next = node.Next.Next. The duplicate node is unlinked, leaving exactly one copy of . The list is one shorter and the target is effectively deleted.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-detect-loop::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-detect-loop', 'Which approach fits "Detect loop"?', 'Fast laps slow inside the loop; reset one to head, walk in lockstep to the entry', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-detect-loop::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-detect-loop', 'On the "WALK" step (slow=, fast=), what happens?', 'Walk in lockstep: slow → index , fast → index . They are still apart, so keep advancing both by one.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-detect-loop::state', 'prep-linked-lists-detect-loop', 'What does the `loopAt` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `loopAt` in sync: where the chain reconnects (-1 = none)', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-detect-loop::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-detect-loop', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Detect loop"?', 'O(n). O(1). meet -> slow=head; advance both by 1 until equal', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-detect-loop::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-detect-loop', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'slow and fast meet again at index  (value ) — that is the start of the loop. Return this node.', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists', 'Which approach fits "Find intersection of two lists"?', 'Each pointer hops to the other list''s head; they meet at the junction', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists', 'On the "FOUND" step (node ), what happens?', 'pa == pb at the shared node  — that is the intersection where both lists merge. Return it.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists::state', 'prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists', 'What does the `cells` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cells` in sync: the rendered chain, left → right', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find intersection of two lists"?', 'O(n). O(1). pa: a then b, pb: b then a, until pa==pb', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-find-intersection-of-two-lists', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'pa == pb at the shared node  — that is the intersection where both lists merge. Return it.', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'Which approach fits "Find node"?', 'Walk the list until a node''s value matches', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::init', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'At the start of a run (Find node), what strategy is established?', 'Find node: walk the linked list from the head, one node at a time, and return the first node whose value equals . A single linear scan — O(n) time, O(1) space.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'On the "FOUND" step (match @), what happens?', 'Match — the node at position  holds , which equals . Return this node.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::state', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'What does the `head` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `head` in sync: index of the node `head` currently points at; null = past the end', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find node"?', 'O(n). O(1). while head: head.Val==val? else head=head.Next', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-find-node::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-find-node', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', ' != , so this is not the node. Advance: head = head.Next, moving on to the next link in the chain.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'Which approach fits "Flatten doubly linked list"?', 'DFS preorder: splice each child list in before moving to the sibling', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::init', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'At the start of a run (Flatten doubly linked list), what strategy is established?', 'Flatten the multilevel doubly linked list into a single level. We DFS in preorder: each time a node has a child, splice that whole child sublist in right after it, then continue with the saved next. We keep a running tail "prev" and link prev↔node as we go.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'On the "DESCEND" step (child of ), what happens?', ' has a child list. Recurse into the child first (DFS), flatten it, and remember its tail so we can re-attach the saved next afterwards.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::state', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'What does the `prevPos` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `prevPos` in sync: position in `chain` of the running tail (`prev`)', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Flatten doubly linked list"?', 'O(n). O(h). link prev<->node; recurse child then next; keep tail as prev', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-flatten-doubly-linked-list', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every level is spliced into one chain. The flattened order is . Time O(n) — each node visited once; Space O(h) — recursion depth is the multilevel height.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'Which approach fits "Insert into a Sorted Circular Linked List"?', 'Three cases for insertion between `prev` and `curr`:', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::init', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'At the start of a run (Insert into a Sorted Circular Linked List), what strategy is established?', 'Insert  into the sorted circular list. Walk pairs (prev, cur) starting at head until we find the gap where  fits. prev = head (index 0), cur = the next node.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'On the "CASE2" step ( is new ), what happens?', 'Case 2:  ${insertVal >= pv ? ', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::state', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'What does the `chain` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chain` in sync: the (possibly grown) list values in order', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Insert into a Sorted Circular Linked List"?', 'O(n). O(1). Three cases for insertion between `prev` and `curr`:', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-insert-into-a-sorted-circular-linked-list', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Splice the new node between  and : prev.Next = node, node.Next = cur. With all values equal the order is unchanged.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'Which approach fits "Last men standing"?', 'Stand in a circle; skip k-1, drop the kth, repeat to the survivor', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::init', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'At the start of a run (Last men standing), what strategy is established?', 'Josephus circle:  people stand in a ring numbered 1... Starting the count, every -th person is eliminated; repeat until one survivor remains. We simulate a circular linked list where cur walks k−1 steps then drops cur.Next.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'On the "MARK" step (drop ), what happens?', 'cur is on person ; the very next person, , is the k-th in this count and gets eliminated. In the list this is cur.Next = cur.Next.Next.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::state', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'What does the `curIdx` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `curIdx` in sync: position of `cur` within ring', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Last men standing"?', 'O(n*k). O(1). advance k-1 steps; cur.Next=cur.Next.Next', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-last-men-standing', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'One person is left: person  is the last one standing. With n=, k= the answer is .', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'Which approach fits "Merge K sorted lists"?', 'Pairwise-merge the lists until a single list remains', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::init', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'At the start of a run (Merge K sorted lists), what strategy is established?', 'Merge K Sorted Lists: we have  already-sorted lists. Repeatedly pair them up and merge two at a time — pool size roughly halves each round — until a single sorted list remains. Time O(n log k), Space O(k).', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'On the "TAKE_B" step (take ), what happens?', 'Compare heads: a= ≥ b=, so splice node  from list B onto the chain and advance B. (Ties take B, matching the Go else-branch.)', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::state', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'What does the `round` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `round` in sync: pass number through the while(len>1) loop', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Merge K sorted lists"?', 'O(n log k). O(k). while len>1: merge i with i+1 into a new slice', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-k-sorted-lists', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Pair done: lists  and  merged into . Add it to the next pool.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'Which approach fits "Merge two sorted lists"?', 'Zip two sorted lists, always attaching the smaller head', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::init', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'At the start of a run (Merge two sorted lists), what strategy is established?', 'Merge two sorted lists: zip them into one sorted chain. We keep a dummy head and a cur pointer, then repeatedly attach the smaller of the two current heads. List 1 = [], list 2 = [].', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'On the "ATTACH_L2" step (take ), what happens?', 'l2''s head () is smaller or equal, so attach it and advance l2''s head. cur moves to the appended node.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::state', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'What does the `l1` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `l1` in sync: original list 1 values (left→right chain)', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Merge two sorted lists"?', 'O(n). O(1). dummy; while both attach min; append leftover', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-merge-two-sorted-lists', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'One list ran out, so the merge is complete. Return dummy.Next — the fully merged sorted chain [].', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'Which approach fits "Print from end"?', 'Recurse to the tail, then append while the stack unwinds', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::init', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'At the start of a run (Print from end), what strategy is established?', 'Print from end: recurse all the way to the tail first, then append each value as the call stack unwinds. out = rec(next); out = append(out, head.Val). The result lists the values back-to-front.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'On the "UNWIND" step (append ), what happens?', 'The deeper call returned, so node ''s call resumes and appends its value  to the output. Because the tail finished first, values come out in reverse order.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::state', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'What does the `values` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `values` in sync: the linked list node values, head → tail', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Print from end"?', 'O(n). O(n). out=rec(next); out=append(out,head.Val)', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-print-from-end::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-print-from-end', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All calls have unwound. The output is the node values reversed: [].', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'Which approach fits "Reverse linked list"?', 'Flip each Next to point back at prev as you walk', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::init', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'At the start of a run (Reverse linked list), what strategy is established?', 'Reverse a singly linked list in place. We walk it once with three pointers: prev starts at nil, head (cur) starts at the first node, and next is a scratch pointer. Each step flips one node''s link to point backward.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'On the "FLIP" step (→), what happens?', 'Flip the link: head.Next = prev, so node  now points back at  instead of forward. This is the actual reversal.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::state', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'What does the `values` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `values` in sync: node values, fixed positions left→right (original order)', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Reverse linked list"?', 'O(n). O(1). next=head.Next; head.Next=prev; prev=head; head=next', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-linked-list', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'head reached nil, so the walk is complete. prev now points at the old tail, which is the new head of the reversed list. Return prev. Time O(n), Space O(1).', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'Which approach fits "Reverse Nodes in k-Group"?', 'Use a dummy node before head. For each group:', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::init', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'At the start of a run (Reverse Nodes in k-Group), what strategy is established?', 'Reverse Nodes in k-Group: walk the list and reverse every block of  consecutive nodes, leaving any final block shorter than  untouched. A dummy node (D) sits before the head so the first group has a stable predecessor.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'On the "REVERSE" step (swap ↔), what happens?', 'Reversing the group with the prev/cur finger dance: flip the order of the values at the two ends of the remaining slice (positions  and ).', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::state', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'What does the `groupPrev` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `groupPrev` in sync: node before the group being processed', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Reverse Nodes in k-Group"?', 'O(n). O(1). Use a dummy node before head. For each group:', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-reverse-nodes-in-k-group', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Group reversed. The anchor now points at the old kth node (value ), and the old group head (value ) becomes the anchor for the next group.', 5),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::pattern', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'Which approach fits "Sort linked list"?', 'Split at the middle, sort each half, merge them back', 0),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::init', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'At the start of a run (Sort linked list), what strategy is established?', 'Sort linked list with merge sort: repeatedly split the list at its middle (slow/fast pointers), sort each half recursively, then merge the two sorted halves back together. The chain below shows the node values left→right.', 1),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::key-step', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'On the "COMPARE" step ( < ), what happens?', ' (left) <  (right), so append  to the merged list and advance the left pointer.', 2),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::state', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'What does the `chain` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `chain` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::complexity', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Sort linked list"?', 'O(n log n). O(1). slow/fast split; recurse both; mergeSorted', 4),
  ('prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list::outcome', 'prep-linked-lists-sort-linked-list', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every half has been merged. The full list is sorted: []. Time O(n log n), space O(1) extra for the in-place linked-list merge.', 5),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::pattern', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'Which approach fits "Add binary"?', 'Add right-to-left with a carry bit (base 2)', 0),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::init', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'At the start of a run (Add binary), what strategy is established?', 'Add binary: add the two binary strings "" and "" like grade-school addition, but in base 2. Walk both from the rightmost bit, keeping a carry.', 1),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::key-step', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'On the "EMIT" step (bit , carry ), what happens?', 'Prepend bit  to the answer, giving "". Carry  moves into the next column to the left.', 2),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::state', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index into a (-1 = past the front)', 3),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::complexity', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Add binary"?', 'O(max(len)). O(max(len)). sum=a+b+carry; bit=sum%2; carry=sum/2; reverse', 4),
  ('prep-math-add-binary::outcome', 'prep-math-add-binary', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'No bits and no carry remain. Reversing the LSB-first bits gives the sum "".', 5),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::pattern', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'Which approach fits "Add two big string numbers"?', 'Same as binary add, but base 10', 0),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::init', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'At the start of a run (Add two big string numbers), what strategy is established?', 'Big-integer addition: the numbers are too long for a machine int, so we add them digit by digit as strings. Walk both numbers from the least-significant digit (the right end), keeping a running carry.', 1),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::key-step', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'On the "WRITE" step (digit=, carry=), what happens?', 'Keep sum % 10 =  as this column''s output digit, and carry sum / 10 =  into the next column. Digits collected so far (least-significant first): .', 2),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::state', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current digit index into a (from the right)', 3),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::complexity', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Add two big string numbers"?', 'O(max(len)). O(max(len)). sum=a+b+carry; digit=sum%10; carry=sum/10; reverse', 4),
  ('prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers::outcome', 'prep-math-add-two-big-string-numbers', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every column is processed and the carry is gone. The digits were appended least-significant first, so reverse them to get the answer: .', 5),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::pattern', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'Which approach fits "Base 26 encoding"?', 'Excel columns: A=1..Z=26, then AA; decrement before each mod', 0),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::init', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'At the start of a run (Base 26 encoding), what strategy is established?', 'Base-26 (Excel-column) encoding of n = . This is a bijective base 26 where A=1..Z=26 and there is no zero digit, so each step decrements n by 1 before taking n % 26. We peel off one letter per step, least-significant first, then reverse.', 1),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::key-step', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'On the "DIGIT" step (→), what happens?', 'Take the least-significant base-26 digit:  % 26 = , which is the letter '''' (''A'' + ). Append it to the output buffer.', 2),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::state', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'What does the `n0` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `n0` in sync: the original number being encoded', 3),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::complexity', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Base 26 encoding"?', 'O(log n). O(log n). while n>0: n--; out+=''A''+n%26; n/=26; reverse', 4),
  ('prep-math-base-26-encoding::outcome', 'prep-math-base-26-encoding', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Divide down to move to the next-higher digit: n = ⌊ / 26⌋ = . ', 5),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::pattern', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'Which approach fits "Basic Calculator II"?', 'See Basic Calculator Ii pattern', 0),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::init', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'At the start of a run (Basic Calculator II), what strategy is established?', 'Basic Calculator II evaluates "" with + − × ÷ (no parentheses). We scan left to right, building each number, and keep a stack of signed terms. × and ÷ act immediately on the top of the stack; + and − just push. The answer is the sum of the stack.', 1),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::key-step', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'On the "DIGIT" step (num=), what happens?', 'Digit '''' at index : fold it into the running number — num = num×10 +  = . We only act once the number ends.', 2),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::state', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: the expression, one char per cell', 3),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::complexity', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Basic Calculator II"?', 'O(n). O(n). Basic Calculator Ii', 4),
  ('prep-math-basic-calculator-ii::outcome', 'prep-math-basic-calculator-ii', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every term is on the stack: []. Sum them to get the answer: .', 5),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::pattern', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'Which approach fits "Cinema Seat Allocation"?', 'See Cinema Seat Allocation pattern', 0),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::init', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'At the start of a run (Cinema Seat Allocation), what strategy is established?', 'Cinema Seat Allocation: each of  rows has 10 seats. A family needs 4 consecutive seats, and only the three windows 2-5, 4-7 or 6-9 count. At most 2 families fit per row, so start optimistically at 2 x  = . Rows with no reservation keep both groups; we only revisit rows that have a reserved seat.', 1),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::key-step', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'On the "CHECK" step (L= M= R=), what happens?', 'Test the three windows against row : left seats 2-5 , middle seats 4-7 , right seats 6-9 .', 2),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::state', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'What does the `row` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `row` in sync: row currently inspected (null before/after loop)', 3),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::complexity', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Cinema Seat Allocation"?', 'O(reservations). O(reserved rows). Cinema Seat Allocation', 4),
  ('prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation::outcome', 'prep-math-cinema-seat-allocation', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All reserved rows handled (each in O(1) work). The remaining  untouched rows still hold 2 families each. Final answer:  families.', 5),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::pattern', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'Which approach fits "Convert decimal to base N"?', 'Repeated divmod; collect remainders, then reverse', 0),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::init', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'At the start of a run (Convert decimal to base N), what strategy is established?', 'Convert  to base  by repeated divmod: at each step take n %  as the next digit (least-significant first), then divide n by . The digits come out reversed, so we flip them at the end.', 1),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::key-step', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'On the "COLLECTED" step ( digits), what happens?', 'n has been divided down to 0. The collected digits [] are least-significant first, so the number reads correctly only once reversed.', 2),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::state', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'What does the `n` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `n` in sync: original decimal input', 3),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::complexity', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert decimal to base N"?', 'O(log n). O(log n). out+=digits[n%base]; n/=base; reverse', 4),
  ('prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n::outcome', 'prep-math-convert-decimal-to-base-n', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Reverse in place: swap positions  and  so the most-significant digit moves to the front. Now [].', 5),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::pattern', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'Which approach fits "Convert string to integer"?', 'Skip spaces, read sign, consume digits, clamp on overflow', 0),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::init', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'At the start of a run (Convert string to integer), what strategy is established?', 'Parse the string "" into an integer, mimicking atoi: skip leading spaces, read an optional sign, then consume digits left to right building result = result*10 + digit, clamping on overflow.', 1),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::key-step', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'On the "SIGN" step (sign=+1), what happens?', 'No explicit sign at index , so the number defaults to positive.', 2),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::state', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: each character of s, rendered as an ArrayRow cell', 3),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::complexity', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert string to integer"?', 'O(n). O(1). guard result>(max-digit)/10 -> clamp; result=result*10+digit', 4),
  ('prep-math-convert-string-to-integer::outcome', 'prep-math-convert-string-to-integer', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Cursor reached a non-digit or the end of the string. Apply the sign to get the final answer .', 5),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::pattern', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'Which approach fits "Count set bits in number"?', 'n & (n-1) drops the lowest 1 each iteration', 0),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::init', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'At the start of a run (Count set bits in number), what strategy is established?', 'Count the set (1) bits in  using Brian Kernighan''s trick: n & (n − 1) clears the lowest set bit. Each time we do that, we''ve removed exactly one 1, so we count one loop per set bit.', 1),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::key-step', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'On the "CLEAR" step (n=, count=), what happens?', 'n & (n − 1) =  &  = : the lowest 1 is gone. Increment count to . Continue while n is still non-zero.', 2),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::state', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'What does the `original` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `original` in sync: the number we started with (for the header)', 3),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::complexity', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Count set bits in number"?', 'O(bits set). O(1). count=0; while n!=0 { n&=n-1; count++ }', 4),
  ('prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number::outcome', 'prep-math-count-set-bits-in-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'n has reached 0, so every 1 bit has been cleared and counted.  has  set bit. Time O(bits set), Space O(1).', 5),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::pattern', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'Which approach fits "Covert integer to roman numeral"?', 'Greedily subtract the largest symbol value that fits', 0),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::init', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'At the start of a run (Covert integer to roman numeral), what strategy is established?', 'Integer → Roman: greedily subtract the largest symbol value that still fits. We walk the value table (1000, 900, 500, 400, …, 1) once, and for each value repeatedly emit its symbol while it is ≤ the remaining number.', 1),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::key-step', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'On the "SKIP" step ( < ), what happens?', 'Now  < , so  no longer fits. Move down to the next-smaller symbol.', 2),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::state', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'What does the `original` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `original` in sync: the number we started with', 3),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::complexity', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Covert integer to roman numeral"?', 'O(1). O(1). values/symbols incl 900,400,90,40,9,4; while num>=v emit symbol', 4),
  ('prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral::outcome', 'prep-math-covert-integer-to-roman-numeral', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Remaining number is 0 — everything has been converted. The Roman numeral is complete: "".', 5),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::pattern', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'Which approach fits "Factorial number"?', 'Multiply 1..n into an accumulator', 0),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::init', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'At the start of a run (Factorial number), what strategy is established?', 'Factorial number: compute n! = 1·2·3·…·n iteratively. Start an accumulator result = 1, then fold each factor from 2 up to  into it. Time O(n), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::key-step', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'On the "MUL" step (× → ), what happens?', 'Multiply factor  into the accumulator: result =  ×  = . This folds  into the running product 1·2·…·.', 2),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::state', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'What does the `factors` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `factors` in sync: the multiplicands 2..n laid out as a row', 3),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::complexity', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Factorial number"?', 'O(n). O(1). result=1; for i=2..n result*=i', 4),
  ('prep-math-factorial-number::outcome', 'prep-math-factorial-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All factors up to  have been multiplied in. ! = .', 5),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::pattern', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'Which approach fits "Fibonacci number"?', 'Slide the pair (a,b) -> (b, a+b)', 0),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::init', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'At the start of a run (Fibonacci number), what strategy is established?', 'Fibonacci: F(n) = F(n−1) + F(n−2). We iterate in O(n) time and O(1) space, carrying just two rolling values (prev, cur) and sliding the pair (a, b) → (b, a+b) each step.', 1),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::key-step', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'On the "SEED" step (prev=0, cur=1), what happens?', 'Seed the pair with the first two Fibonacci numbers: prev = F(0) = 0 and cur = F(1) = 1. We now roll forward from i = 2.', 2),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::state', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'What does the `seq` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `seq` in sync: Fibonacci values computed so far, seq[k] = F(k)', 3),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::complexity', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Fibonacci number"?', 'O(n). O(1). prev,cur=0,1; cur=prev+cur; n<=1 return n', 4),
  ('prep-math-fibonacci-number::outcome', 'prep-math-fibonacci-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The window reached i = . cur now holds F() = , which is the answer.', 5),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::pattern', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'Which approach fits "Find missing number"?', 'XOR all indices and values with n; everything cancels but the gap', 0),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::init', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'At the start of a run (Find missing number), what strategy is established?', 'Find Missing Number: the array holds n distinct values from 0..n with exactly one gap. XOR is self-cancelling (x ^ x = 0), so if we XOR every index 0..n together with every value, each present number pairs off and vanishes — leaving only the missing one. Seed the accumulator with n =  (the one index that has no cell). Time O(n), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::key-step', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'On the "FOLD" step (^= ^), what happens?', 'Index  holds value . Fold both in: xorAll ^=  ^  (= ).  ^  = . Every number that IS present will get XORed an even number of times overall and cancel to 0.', 2),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::state', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being folded in', 3),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::complexity', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find missing number"?', 'O(n). O(1). xorAll=n; xorAll ^= i ^ v for each', 4),
  ('prep-math-find-missing-number::outcome', 'prep-math-find-missing-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All indices and values are folded in. Everything cancelled except the number that never appeared as a value — the accumulator is , so the missing number is .', 5),
  ('prep-math-find-single-number::pattern', 'prep-math-find-single-number', 'Which approach fits "Find single number"?', 'Pairs cancel under XOR; the lonely value survives', 0),
  ('prep-math-find-single-number::key-step', 'prep-math-find-single-number', 'On the "XOR" step (acc^=), what happens?', 'Fold in nums[] = : acc =  ^  = . XOR compares bit by bit — matching bits become 0, differing bits become 1.${
        canceled
          ? ', 1),
  ('prep-math-find-single-number::state', 'prep-math-find-single-number', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: index of the value being folded in this frame', 2),
  ('prep-math-find-single-number::complexity', 'prep-math-find-single-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find single number"?', 'O(n). O(1). acc=0; acc^=each num; return acc', 3),
  ('prep-math-find-single-number::outcome', 'prep-math-find-single-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every duplicate paired off to 0, so what remains is the single number: . This ran in O(n) time and O(1) space — one accumulator, one pass.', 4),
  ('prep-math-fizzbuzz::pattern', 'prep-math-fizzbuzz', 'Which approach fits "Fizzbuzz"?', 'Check %15 first, then %3, then %5', 0),
  ('prep-math-fizzbuzz::init', 'prep-math-fizzbuzz', 'At the start of a run (Fizzbuzz), what strategy is established?', 'FizzBuzz: for every number 1.. we print "FizzBuzz" if it is divisible by 15, else "Fizz" if divisible by 3, else "Buzz" if divisible by 5, otherwise the number itself. Order matters — the 15 check must come first.', 1),
  ('prep-math-fizzbuzz::state', 'prep-math-fizzbuzz', 'What does the `out` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `out` in sync: filled results so far; '''' = not filled yet', 2),
  ('prep-math-fizzbuzz::complexity', 'prep-math-fizzbuzz', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Fizzbuzz"?', 'O(n). O(n). 15 FizzBuzz; 3 Fizz; 5 Buzz; else the number', 3),
  ('prep-math-fizzbuzz::outcome', 'prep-math-fizzbuzz', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every number from 1 to  has been classified and placed. The output array holds  strings — that is the complete FizzBuzz sequence.', 4),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::pattern', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'Which approach fits "Hamming distance"?', 'x^y highlights the differing bits; count them', 0),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::init', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'At the start of a run (Hamming distance), what strategy is established?', 'Hamming distance counts the bit positions where x and y differ. x =  = ₂ and y =  = ₂ (shown MSB first). We compare them one bit at a time using XOR.', 1),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::key-step', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'On the "POP" step (count=), what happens?', 'Brian Kernighan trick: xor &= xor − 1 clears the lowest set 1-bit (position ). Each clear is one differing bit, so bump count to . xor is now ₂.', 2),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::state', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'What does the `width` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `width` in sync: number of bit columns rendered (MSB first)', 3),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::complexity', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Hamming distance"?', 'O(1). O(1). xor=x^y; popcount via xor&=xor-1', 4),
  ('prep-math-hamming-distance::outcome', 'prep-math-hamming-distance', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'xor reached 0, so every differing bit has been counted. The Hamming distance between  and  is . Runs in O(1) time and O(1) space for fixed-width ints.', 5),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::pattern', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'Which approach fits "Integer to English Words"?', 'See Integer To English Words pattern', 0),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::init', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'At the start of a run (Integer to English Words), what strategy is established?', 'Integer to English Words: read  out loud. The trick is to chop the number into 3-digit groups from the right — ones, then Thousand, Million, Billion — name each group, then glue the scale words back on.', 1),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::key-step', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'On the "NAME" step (""), what happens?', 'Name the 3-digit group  with the lookup helper:  → "". Hundreds use below-20 + "Hundred"; the last two digits use the tens/below-20 tables.', 2),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::state', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'What does the `chunks` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chunks` in sync: groups of 3 digits, index 0 = least significant (ones)', 3),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::complexity', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Integer to English Words"?', 'O(1). O(1). Integer To English Words', 4),
  ('prep-math-integer-to-english-words::outcome', 'prep-math-integer-to-english-words', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'More-significant groups are spoken first, so put "" at the front of the phrase. Running phrase: "".', 5),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::pattern', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'Which approach fits "Is binary"?', 'At most one bit set means n&(n-1) is zero', 0),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::init', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'At the start of a run (Is binary), what strategy is established?', 'Is Binary asks whether n is a power of two — a number with exactly one bit set. The trick is a single-bit check: n > 0 && (n & (n-1)) == 0. Time O(1), space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::key-step', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'On the "MINUS" step (n-1=), what happens?', 'Subtracting one flips the lowest set bit of  to 0 and turns every bit below it into 1. So n-1 = . If  had a single set bit, that bit is now gone and all lower bits are 1 — the two numbers share no bits.', 2),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::state', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'What does the `sign` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `sign` in sync: -1 = not yet checked, 0 = fails n>0, 1 = passes n>0', 3),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::complexity', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is binary"?', 'O(1). O(1). n>0 && n&(n-1)==0', 4),
  ('prep-math-is-binary::outcome', 'prep-math-is-binary', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Bit : n has  and n-1 has , so their AND is .', 5),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::pattern', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'Which approach fits "Is odd number"?', 'Lowest bit set means the number is odd', 0),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::init', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'At the start of a run (Is odd number), what strategy is established?', 'Is Odd Number: decide if  is odd. A number''s parity is decided entirely by its lowest binary bit — the 1s place. We never need to divide; the mask n & 1 reads that single bit in O(1) time and O(1) space.', 1),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::key-step', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'On the "READ_LOW" step (bit0=), what happens?', 'Look only at the lowest bit (index , the 1s place): it is . This is exactly what n & 1 isolates — it zeroes out every higher bit and keeps just this one.', 2),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::state', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'What does the `bits` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `bits` in sync: binary digits, most-significant first', 3),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::complexity', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is odd number"?', 'O(1). O(1). return n&1 == 1', 4),
  ('prep-math-is-odd-number::outcome', 'prep-math-is-odd-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Compute the mask:  & 1 = . AND-ing with 1 (binary …0001) discards all higher bits and returns the value of the lowest bit.', 5),
  ('prep-math-is-palindromic-number::pattern', 'prep-math-is-palindromic-number', 'Which approach fits "Is palindromic number"?', 'Reverse only the back half; meet in the middle', 0),
  ('prep-math-is-palindromic-number::init', 'prep-math-is-palindromic-number', 'At the start of a run (Is palindromic number), what strategy is established?', 'Is  a palindrome? We reverse only the back half of the number: build rev by peeling the last digit of n each step, and stop once rev catches up to n. That is O(log n) time and O(1) space — no string conversion.', 1),
  ('prep-math-is-palindromic-number::key-step', 'prep-math-is-palindromic-number', 'On the "PEEL" step (rev=), what happens?', 'Peel the last digit  off n and push it onto rev: rev = rev·10 +  = , then drop it from n so n = . Loop continues while n () > rev ().', 2),
