  ('prep-math-random-number-not-in-array::outcome', 'prep-math-random-number-not-in-array', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Value  is free but k =  > 0, so this is not yet our slot. Consume one free slot: k becomes .', 5),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::pattern', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'Which approach fits "Reverse number"?', 'Pop the last digit and push it onto the reversed value', 0),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::init', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'At the start of a run (Reverse number), what strategy is established?', 'Reverse Number: flip the digit order of . We peel the last digit off n with n % 10 and push it onto a growing reversed value rev, then drop that digit with n /= 10. Sign is handled separately.', 1),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::key-step', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'On the "DIV" step (/10 → ), what happens?', 'Drop that digit with integer division: n =  / 10 = . ', 2),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::state', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'What does the `original` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `original` in sync: the input, signed', 3),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::complexity', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Reverse number"?', 'O(log n). O(1). rev=rev*10+n%10; n/=10', 4),
  ('prep-math-reverse-number::outcome', 'prep-math-reverse-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'n reached 0, so every digit has been moved. rev = ${neg ? ', 5),
  ('prep-math-square-root::pattern', 'prep-math-square-root', 'Which approach fits "Square root"?', 'Binary search the answer in [1, x/2]', 0),
  ('prep-math-square-root::init', 'prep-math-square-root', 'At the start of a run (Square root), what strategy is established?', 'Square Root: compute floor(√) — the largest integer whose square is at most . Instead of scanning, we binary-search the answer in the range [1, ⌊x/2⌋]. Time O(log x), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-math-square-root::key-step', 'prep-math-square-root', 'On the "MID" step (mid=), what happens?', 'Pick mid = lo + (hi−lo)/2 = . Test whether mid fits: compare mid ≤ ⌊/mid⌋ = ⌊/⌋ =  (an overflow-safe way to ask mid·mid ≤ ).', 2),
  ('prep-math-square-root::state', 'prep-math-square-root', 'What does the `ans` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `ans` in sync: best integer whose square is <= x so far', 3),
  ('prep-math-square-root::complexity', 'prep-math-square-root', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Square root"?', 'O(log x). O(1). mid<=x/mid -> ans=mid, lo=mid+1; else hi=mid-1', 4),
  ('prep-math-square-root::outcome', 'prep-math-square-root', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'lo passed hi, so the search is done. The largest integer whose square is ≤  is . floor(√) = .', 5),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::pattern', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'Which approach fits "Sum of digits"?', 'Strip digits one at a time with %10 and /10', 0),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::init', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'At the start of a run (Sum of digits), what strategy is established?', 'Sum of digits: add up every decimal digit of . We strip one digit at a time from the right using n % 10, then drop it with n / 10, until nothing is left. Time O(log n), space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::key-step', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'On the "PEEL" step (+ → sum=), what happens?', 'Peel the last digit:  % 10 = . Add it to the running total → sum = .', 2),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::state', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'What does the `original` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `original` in sync: the input value, kept for display', 3),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::complexity', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Sum of digits"?', 'O(log n). O(1). sum=0; while n>0 { sum+=n%10; n/=10 }', 4),
  ('prep-math-sum-of-digits::outcome', 'prep-math-sum-of-digits', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'n reached 0 — every digit has been added. The digit sum of  is .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::pattern', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'Which approach fits "Battleships in a Board"?', 'See Battleships In A Board pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::init', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'At the start of a run (Battleships in a Board), what strategy is established?', 'Battleships in a Board: count how many ships (''X'' runs) sit on the grid. The trick is a single O(m·n) pass with no extra space — count only a ship''s top-left corner: an ''X'' whose neighbours above and to the left are NOT ''X''.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::key-step', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'On the "CORNER" step (ship #), what happens?', 'Cell (, ) is ''X'' and both its top neighbour ${i === 0 ? ''(off-board)'' : ', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::state', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current row', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::complexity', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Battleships in a Board"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). Battleships In A Board', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board::outcome', 'prep-matrices-battleships-in-a-board', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Finished the single pass over all  cells. Each ship was counted exactly once at its top-left corner, giving  battleship.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::pattern', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'Which approach fits "Check if Word Can Be Placed In Crossword"?', 'See Check If Word Can Be Placed In Crossword pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::init', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'At the start of a run (Check if Word Can Be Placed In Crossword), what strategy is established?', 'Check if Word Can Be Placed In Crossword: slide "" into any horizontal or vertical slot. Scan every row, then every column, breaking each line into segments at ''#'' walls, and test each full-length segment forward and backward. Time O(m·n), Space O(max(m,n)).', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::key-step', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'On the "PLACE" step (row  ), what happens?', '"" fits this horizontal slot in row  (). The word can be placed — return true.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::state', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'What does the `board` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `board` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::complexity', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Check if Word Can Be Placed In Crossword"?', 'O(m·n). O(max(m,n)). Check If Word Can Be Placed In Crossword', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword::outcome', 'prep-matrices-check-if-word-can-be-placed-in-crossword', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', '"" fits this vertical slot in column  (). The word can be placed — return true.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::pattern', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'Which approach fits "Diagonal Traverse"?', 'See Diagonal Traverse pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::init', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'At the start of a run (Diagonal Traverse), what strategy is established?', 'Diagonal Traverse: walk the × matrix along its anti-diagonals in a zig-zag. Start at (0,0) heading . Each diagonal is read in alternating direction. Time O(m·n), O(1) extra.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::key-step', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'On the "STEP" step (↗ to (,)), what happens?', 'Continue up-right: r−1, c+1 → (,). Still inside the grid, keep going .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::state', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'What does the `r` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `r` in sync: current row', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::complexity', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Diagonal Traverse"?', 'O(m·n). O(1) extra. Diagonal Traverse', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse::outcome', 'prep-matrices-diagonal-traverse', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every one of the  cells has been read exactly once. The diagonal order is [].', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::pattern', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'Which approach fits "Fill rows and columns with 1s"?', 'Use row0 and col0 as marker lanes for which rows/cols become 1', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::init', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'At the start of a run (Fill rows and columns with 1s), what strategy is established?', 'Goal: for every cell that holds a 1, set its whole row and whole column to 1. We do it in O(1) extra space by reusing row 0 and column 0 as marker lanes — but first we must remember whether they already contained a 1 of their own.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::key-step', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'On the "APPLY" step (fill ,), what happens?', 'mat[][0] =  or mat[0][] =  flags this cell, so set mat[][] = 1', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::state', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'What does the `mat` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `mat` in sync: current matrix snapshot', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::complexity', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Fill rows and columns with 1s"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). flag row0/col0 first; mark from inside; apply; then borders', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s::outcome', 'prep-matrices-fill-rows-and-columns-with-1s', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every row and column that originally held a 1 is now completely filled, using only row 0 and column 0 as scratch space. The matrix now has  ones.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::pattern', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'Which approach fits "Find path between cells"?', 'DFS in 4 directions building a path, backtracking on dead ends', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::init', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'At the start of a run (Find path between cells), what strategy is established?', 'Find a path from the start cell (,) to the destination (,) through open cells (0). Cells marked 1 are walls. We run DFS in the order right, down, left, up, pushing each cell onto the path and backtracking (popping) when a branch dead-ends.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::key-step', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'On the "FOUND" step (reached (,)), what happens?', 'Cell (,) is the destination. The whole path from start to here is the answer — unwind the recursion returning true.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::state', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'What does the `visited` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `visited` in sync: cells we have committed to and explored from', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::complexity', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find path between cells"?', 'O(m·n). O(m·n). append cell; dest -> true; else recurse; pop on failure', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells::outcome', 'prep-matrices-find-path-between-cells', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every direction out of (,) dead-ended, so pop it off the path and backtrack to the previous cell.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::pattern', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'Which approach fits "Longest increasing path"?', 'DFS only to strictly larger neighbors, caching each cell''s best', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::init', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'At the start of a run (Longest increasing path), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Increasing Path: find the longest run of strictly increasing values, moving up/down/left/right. We DFS from each cell, only stepping to larger neighbors, and cache each cell''s best length in memo so we never recompute it (Time O(m·n), Space O(m·n)).', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::key-step', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'On the "EXTEND" step (best=), what happens?', 'The path through (,) gives length , which beats the current best for (,). Update best = .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::state', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'What does the `memo` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `memo` in sync: memo[i][j] = best path length from cell (i,j); 0 = unfilled', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::complexity', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest increasing path"?', 'O(m·n). O(m·n). memo[i][j]=1+max(dfs over greater neighbors)', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path::outcome', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every cell has been solved and cached. The longest strictly increasing path in the matrix has length .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::pattern', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'Which approach fits "Longest Increasing Path in a Matrix"?', 'See Longest Increasing Path In A Matrix pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::init', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'At the start of a run (Longest Increasing Path in a Matrix), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Increasing Path: from any cell we may step to an orthogonal neighbor only if its value is strictly larger. We want the longest such chain. dfs(r,c) returns the longest increasing path that STARTS at (r,c); we memoize it so each cell is solved once — Time O(m·n), Space O(m·n).', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::key-step', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'On the "BLOCK" step ((,) not >), what happens?', 'Neighbor (,)= is not strictly greater than , so the path cannot increase in that direction. Skip it.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::state', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'What does the `memo` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `memo` in sync: memo[r][c] = longest increasing path starting at (r,c); 0 = not filled', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::complexity', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest Increasing Path in a Matrix"?', 'O(m·n). O(m·n). Longest Increasing Path In A Matrix', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix::outcome', 'prep-matrices-longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every cell has been solved and cached. The longest strictly increasing path anywhere in the matrix has length .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::pattern', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'Which approach fits "Longest Line of Consecutive One in Matrix"?', 'See Longest Line Of Consecutive One In Matrix pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::init', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'At the start of a run (Longest Line of Consecutive One in Matrix), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Line of Consecutive One: find the longest run of 1s in any of 4 directions — horizontal →, vertical ↓, diagonal ↘, or anti-diagonal ↙. We sweep the matrix once, and for each 1 we extend the run from its neighbours, keeping only the previous row in memory.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::key-step', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'On the "ZERO" step ((,)=0), what happens?', 'Cell (,) is a 0, so no line can pass through it. All four direction lengths reset to 0 here.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::state', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'What does the `cur` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cur` in sync: current cell being processed', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::complexity', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest Line of Consecutive One in Matrix"?', 'O(m·n). O(n). Longest Line Of Consecutive One In Matrix', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix::outcome', 'prep-matrices-longest-line-of-consecutive-one-in-matrix', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Sweep complete. The longest line of consecutive 1s in any direction is .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::pattern', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'Which approach fits "Max region"?', 'Flood fill including diagonals; track the largest component', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::init', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'At the start of a run (Max region), what strategy is established?', 'Max Region: find the largest blob of connected 1s, where connectivity counts all 8 neighbours (orthogonal AND diagonal). Scan the grid; every time we hit an unclaimed 1 we flood-fill its whole region and measure its area, keeping the biggest. Time O(m·n), Space O(m·n) for the recursion stack.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::key-step', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'On the "VISIT" step (area=), what happens?', 'Visit (, ) — it is part of this region, so add 1. Region area is now . Next, look at all 8 neighbours and queue any that are still unclaimed land.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::state', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: current cell DFS is inspecting', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::complexity', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Max region"?', 'O(m·n). O(m·n). 8 neighbors; area=1+sum(dfs); keep max', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-max-region::outcome', 'prep-matrices-max-region', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every cell has been scanned. The largest 8-connected region has area .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::pattern', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'Which approach fits "Min distance of meeting point"?', 'Project points onto each axis; the optimal meeting line is the median', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::init', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'At the start of a run (Min distance of meeting point), what strategy is established?', 'Every 1-cell is a person who must walk (Manhattan steps) to one shared meeting cell. Manhattan distance splits cleanly: total cost = (cost along rows) + (cost along columns), so we solve each axis independently. There are  people on this × grid.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::key-step', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'On the "PINCH" step (+), what happens?', 'Pair the outermost s a[lo]= and a[hi]=. Sliding everyone in this span of  gaps toward the center closes min(, )= on each gap, adding ×=. Running  distance = .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::state', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'What does the `rows` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `rows` in sync: grid height', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::complexity', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Min distance of meeting point"?', 'O(n log n) per axis. O(n). sort coords; two-pointer add min*(hi-lo); sum both axes', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point::outcome', 'prep-matrices-min-distance-of-meeting-point', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Add the two axes: minimum total distance = rowDist () + colDist () = . The best meeting point is (median row, median column). Time O(n log n) per axis, space O(n).', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-nearest-bikes::pattern', 'prep-matrices-nearest-bikes', 'Which approach fits "Nearest bikes"?', 'Minimum Manhattan distance over every worker-bike pair', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-nearest-bikes::key-step', 'prep-matrices-nearest-bikes', 'On the "SCANNED" step (W B), what happens?', 'Scan complete:  worker(s) and  bike(s) collected. Now compare every worker against every bike and keep the smallest distance.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-nearest-bikes::state', 'prep-matrices-nearest-bikes', 'What does the `grid` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `grid` in sync: row-major chars', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-nearest-bikes::complexity', 'prep-matrices-nearest-bikes', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Nearest bikes"?', 'O(m·n). O(m·n). collect X/Y cells; best=min |dr|+|dc|', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-nearest-bikes::outcome', 'prep-matrices-nearest-bikes', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every worker-bike pair has been compared. The minimum Manhattan distance is .', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::pattern', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'Which approach fits "Print matrix in spiral Order"?', 'Peel top row, right col, bottom row, left col; shrink the four bounds', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::init', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'At the start of a run (Print matrix in spiral Order), what strategy is established?', 'Spiral order: peel the outer ring of a × matrix, then shrink the four boundaries inward and repeat. Bounds start at rows [..] and cols [..].', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::key-step', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'On the "BOTTOM" step (), what happens?', 'Bottom row: walk right → left across row , appending  from (, ).', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::state', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: cell just appended this frame', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::complexity', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Print matrix in spiral Order"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). loop while bounds valid; shrink startR/endR/startC/endC each lap', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order::outcome', 'prep-matrices-print-matrix-in-spiral-order', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Bounds crossed (startR > endR or startC > endC), so every cell has been peeled. Spiral order: [].', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::pattern', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'Which approach fits "Remove All Ones With Row and Column Flips"?', 'See Remove All Ones With Row And Column Flips pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::init', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'At the start of a run (Remove All Ones With Row and Column Flips), what strategy is established?', 'A row flip or column flip toggles a whole line, but it never changes whether two rows agree or disagree in a given column. So every row must end up either identical to row 0 (clear them together) or its exact inverse (flip it first, then clear). We check each row below row 0 against that rule.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::key-step', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'On the "CMP" step (c:  vs ), what happens?', 'Column : grid[][] =   grid[0][] = . ${
          a === b
            ? ', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::state', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'What does the `row` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `row` in sync: row currently being compared against row 0', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::complexity', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Remove All Ones With Row and Column Flips"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). Remove All Ones With Row And Column Flips', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips::outcome', 'prep-matrices-remove-all-ones-with-row-and-column-flips', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Row  is now neither the same as row 0 nor its inverse — it agrees in some columns and disagrees in others. No combination of row/column flips can reconcile that, so the grid can NEVER be fully cleared. Answer: false.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::pattern', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'Which approach fits "Rotate matrix by 90 degrees"?', 'Rotate ring by ring with a 4-corner cyclic swap', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::init', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'At the start of a run (Rotate matrix by 90 degrees), what strategy is established?', 'Rotate the × matrix 90° clockwise in place. We peel it ring by ring; within each ring a single temp lets us cycle four cells at a time (top ← left ← bottom ← right ← saved top).', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::key-step', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'On the "MOVE" step (left←bottom), what happens?', 'Left gets the bottom value: mat[][] ← mat[][] = .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::state', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'What does the `ring` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `ring` in sync: which layer (i) we are rotating', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::complexity', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Rotate matrix by 90 degrees"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). per ring: top <- left <- bottom <- right <- tmp', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees::outcome', 'prep-matrices-rotate-matrix-by-90-degrees', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Right gets the saved top value: mat[][] ← tmp = . The 4-cycle is complete.', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::pattern', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'Which approach fits "Search a 2D Matrix II"?', 'See Search A 2D Matrix Ii pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::init', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'At the start of a run (Search a 2D Matrix II), what strategy is established?', 'Search a 2D Matrix II: every row is sorted left-to-right and every column top-to-bottom. Start at the top-right corner (,) — the only spot that is the largest in its row and smallest in its column, which lets each comparison rule out a whole row or column.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::key-step', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'On the "LEFT" step ( > ), what happens?', ' is bigger than . Everything below in column  is even larger, so this whole column is ruled out — slide left to column .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::state', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'What does the `r` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `r` in sync: current row', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::complexity', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Search a 2D Matrix II"?', 'O(m+n). O(1). Search A 2D Matrix Ii', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii::outcome', 'prep-matrices-search-a-2d-matrix-ii', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', ' is smaller than . Everything to the left in row  is even smaller, so this whole row is ruled out — drop down to row .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::pattern', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'Which approach fits "Search in sorted matrix"?', 'Start top-right; go left when too big, down when too small', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::init', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'At the start of a run (Search in sorted matrix), what strategy is established?', 'Staircase search: each row is sorted left→right and each column top→bottom. Start at the top-right corner (i=0, j=) — the only cell that is both the largest in its row and the smallest in its column, which makes every comparison decisive.', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::key-step', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'On the "LEFT" step (j-- → ), what happens?', ' > , so this whole column is too big at and above this corner — everything below in column  is even larger. Discard the column and move left: j becomes .', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::state', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current row', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::complexity', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Search in sorted matrix"?', 'O(m+n). O(1). i,j=0,n-1; >key -> j--, else i++', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix::outcome', 'prep-matrices-search-in-sorted-matrix', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', ' < , so this whole row is too small from this corner leftward — everything to the left in row  is even smaller. Discard the row and move down: i becomes .', 5),
  ('prep-matrices-spiral-matrix::pattern', 'prep-matrices-spiral-matrix', 'Which approach fits "Spiral Matrix"?', 'See Spiral Matrix pattern', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-spiral-matrix::state', 'prep-matrices-spiral-matrix', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: cell appended this frame', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-spiral-matrix::complexity', 'prep-matrices-spiral-matrix', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Spiral Matrix"?', 'O(m·n). O(1). Spiral Matrix', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::pattern', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'Which approach fits "Word search on board"?', 'DFS from each cell matching the word index, marking and unmarking visited', 0),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::init', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'At the start of a run (Word search on board), what strategy is established?', 'Word search: try to spell "" by walking neighbours (up/down/left/right) on the board, never reusing a cell. We launch a DFS from every cell and backtrack on failure. Time O(m·n·4^s), Space O(s).', 1),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::key-step', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'On the "MARK" step ('''' @(,)), what happens?', 'board[][]='''' matches word[]=''''. Mark it visited and look for word[]='''' among its neighbours.', 2),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::state', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'What does the `idx` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `idx` in sync: how many characters matched so far (word[idx] is the next target)', 3),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::complexity', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Word search on board"?', 'O(m·n·4^s). O(s). idx==len -> true; mark, recurse 4-dir, unmark on fail', 4),
  ('prep-matrices-word-search-on-board::outcome', 'prep-matrices-word-search-on-board', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Launch a fresh DFS from cell (,)='''', attempting to match word[0]='''' here.', 5),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::pattern', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'Which approach fits "Array Manipulation (HackerRank)"?', 'Use a **difference array**: for each query `[a,b,k]`, do `diff[a] += k` and `diff[b+1] -= k`', 0),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::init', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'At the start of a run (Array Manipulation (HackerRank)), what strategy is established?', 'Array Manipulation: start with  zeros, then apply  range-add queries [a,b,k] (each adds k to positions a..b). Instead of touching every cell per query, keep a difference array: diff[a] += k and diff[b+1] -= k mark only the two boundaries where the running total changes.', 1),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::key-step', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'On the "QUERY" step ([,,+]), what happens?', 'Query  = add  to positions ... We record diff[] +=  (the value rises here) and diff[] -=  (it falls right after position ). Only two indices change, regardless of how wide the range is.', 2),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::state', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'What does the `diff` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `diff` in sync: difference array, length n + 2 (1-indexed; index 0 unused)', 3),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::complexity', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Array Manipulation (HackerRank)"?', 'O(n+m). O(n). Use a **difference array**: for each query `[a,b,k]`, do `diff[a] += k` and `diff[b+1] -= k`; Prefix sum of the difference array reconstructs the actual values', 4),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation::outcome', 'prep-prefix-sum-array-manipulation', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The sweep is complete. The largest value any position ever held is  — that is the answer, found in O(n+m) time using only the difference array.', 5),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::pattern', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'Which approach fits "Continuous Subarray Sum"?', '`prefix[j] - prefix[i]` is a multiple of `k` iff `prefix[j] % k == prefix[i] % k`', 0),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::init', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'At the start of a run (Continuous Subarray Sum), what strategy is established?', 'Continuous Subarray Sum: is there a subarray of length >= 2 whose sum is a multiple of ? Key fact: sum(i+1..j) is a multiple of  exactly when prefix[j] %  == prefix[i] % . We seed the map with remainder 0 -> index -1 so a whole prefix that is itself a multiple counts.', 1),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::key-step', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'On the "TOOSHORT" step (gap <2), what happens?', 'Remainder  was last seen at index , but  −  =  < 2, so the subarray would have length 1. Keep the earlier index  (we want the first occurrence) and move on.', 2),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::state', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being scanned', 3),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::complexity', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Continuous Subarray Sum"?', 'O(n). O(min(n,k)). `prefix[j] - prefix[i]` is a multiple of `k` iff `prefix[j] % k == prefix[i] % k`; Store first occurrence index of each `prefix % k` in a map; seed `{0: -1}` fo', 4),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum::outcome', 'prep-prefix-sum-continuous-subarray-sum', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Remainder  is new — record map[] =  as its first occurrence so a later match can form a subarray back to here.', 5),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::pattern', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'Which approach fits "Subarray Sum Equals K"?', 'If `prefix[j] - prefix[i] == k`, then subarray `[i+1..j]` sums to `k`', 0),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::init', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'At the start of a run (Subarray Sum Equals K), what strategy is established?', 'Subarray Sum Equals K: count subarrays summing to . Key idea — if prefix[j] − prefix[i] = , then the slice (i+1 .. j) sums to . We scan once, keeping a map of how many times each running prefix sum has occurred. Seed it with {0: 1} so a whole-prefix match counts.', 1),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::key-step', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'On the "MISS" step (+0), what happens?', ' is not in the map, so no subarray ending at index  sums to . The count stays .', 2),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::state', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being processed', 3),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::complexity', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Subarray Sum Equals K"?', 'O(n). O(n). If `prefix[j] - prefix[i] == k`, then subarray `[i+1..j]` sums to `k`; Use a hashmap counting how many times each prefix sum has occurred', 4),
  ('prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k::outcome', 'prep-prefix-sum-subarray-sum-equals-k', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Scan complete.  subarray sum to .', 5),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::pattern', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Window Substring"?', 'Use a frequency array `[128]int` for `t`. Track `required` = total chars still needed', 0),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::init', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Window Substring), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum Window Substring: find the shortest slice of s that contains every character of t (with multiplicity). We slide a window [l, r] over s, tracking need = how many of t''s characters are still missing.', 1),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::key-step', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'On the "COMPLETE" step (len=), what happens?', 'Window [, ] is complete but length  is not shorter than the current best (), so keep the old best and try to shrink.', 2),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::state', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'What does the `s` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `s` in sync: characters of s, one per array cell', 3),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::complexity', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Window Substring"?', 'O(m+n). O(1). Use a frequency array `[128]int` for `t`. Track `required` = total chars still needed; Expand right: if `freq[ch] > 0` before decrement → a needed char found, `', 4),
  ('prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring::outcome', 'prep-sliding-window-minimum-window-substring', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Window [, ] is complete but length  is not shorter than the current best (), so keep the old best and try to shrink.', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::pattern', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'Which approach fits "3Sum"?', 'Sort, then fix `nums[i]`, use two pointers `l=i+1, r=n-1` for the remaining pair', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::init', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'At the start of a run (3Sum), what strategy is established?', '3Sum: find every unique triplet that sums to 0. Strategy: sort the array, then for each fixed anchor nums[i] walk two pointers (l from the left, r from the right) inward to find the remaining pair.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::key-step', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'On the "FIX_I" step (anchor ), what happens?', 'Fix the anchor nums[] = . Set l =  (just right of the anchor) and r =  (the last element); we need nums[l] + nums[r] = .', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::state', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'What does the `nums` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `nums` in sync: the working array (sorted after the sort phase)', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::complexity', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'What are the time and space complexities for "3Sum"?', 'O(n²). O(1). Sort, then fix `nums[i]`, use two pointers `l=i+1, r=n-1` for the remaining pair; Skip duplicates: if `nums[i] == nums[i-1]`, skip `i`; after finding a triplet,', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-3sum::outcome', 'prep-sorting-3sum', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Sum  is above 0, so we need a smaller value. Because the array is sorted, moving r leftward (r → ) decreases the sum.', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::pattern', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'Which approach fits "Equal Sum Arrays with Minimum Number of Operations"?', 'If `min_possible_sum > max_possible_sum` of the other → `-1`', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::init', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'At the start of a run (Equal Sum Arrays with Minimum Number of Operations), what strategy is established?', 'Each value is a die in 1..6. We want sum(nums1) = sum(nums2) using the fewest single-die changes. Start sums: nums1=, nums2=.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::key-step', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'On the "SKIP" step (bucket  empty), what happens?', 'Bucket  is empty — no die can move the gap by . Drop to the next-smaller contribution.', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::state', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'What does the `c` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `c` in sync: contribution bucket currently being processed (5..1)', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::complexity', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Equal Sum Arrays with Minimum Number of Operations"?', 'O(n+m). O(1). If `min_possible_sum > max_possible_sum` of the other → `-1`; Make `nums1` the smaller sum. For each element: max contribution = `6-x` (increase) or `x-1` (decr', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations::outcome', 'prep-sorting-equal-sum-arrays-with-minimum-number-of-operations', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The gap is fully closed using the largest contributions first. Minimum operations = .', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::pattern', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'Which approach fits "Max Chunks To Make Sorted II"?', 'Use a **monotonic stack** storing the max of each chunk', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::init', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'At the start of a run (Max Chunks To Make Sorted II), what strategy is established?', 'Max Chunks To Make Sorted II: split the array into the most chunks so that sorting each chunk independently yields the fully sorted array. We keep a monotonic stack where each entry is the max of one chunk; the final stack size is the answer.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::key-step', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'On the "MERGE" step (pop ), what happens?', 'The top chunk-max  is greater than , so  can''t begin a new chunk — that chunk must absorb it. Pop  and fold it into the running max: max becomes .', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::state', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being processed', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::complexity', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Max Chunks To Make Sorted II"?', 'O(n). O(n). Use a **monotonic stack** storing the max of each chunk; For each `val`: if `val < stack top`, merge chunks (pop) keeping the largest max, then push that max', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii::outcome', 'prep-sorting-max-chunks-to-make-sorted-ii', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every element is placed. The stack holds  chunk-maxima, so the array can be cut into at most  chunk that each sort independently into the final sorted order.', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::pattern', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Deletions to Make Character Frequencies Unique"?', 'Count frequencies, sort descending', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::init', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Deletions to Make Character Frequencies Unique), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum Deletions: every distinct letter''s frequency must be unique. We count each letter''s frequency and sort the counts ascending —  — then process the tallest bars first, shrinking any count that collides with one we''ve already claimed.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::key-step', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'On the "CLAIM" step (claim ), what happens?', 'Frequency  for '''' is free, so claim it — no other letter may use  now.', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::state', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'What does the `bars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `bars` in sync: current freq value of each bar (mutates as we delete)', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::complexity', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Deletions to Make Character Frequencies Unique"?', 'O(n). O(1). Count frequencies, sort descending; For each frequency, if already used, decrement it until it''s unique or 0', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique::outcome', 'prep-sorting-minimum-deletions-to-make-character-frequencies-unique', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All counts are now unique. The minimum number of deletions to make every character frequency unique is .', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::pattern', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'Which approach fits "Sort Integers by The Power Value"?', 'Compute Collatz power for each number with memoization (recursive)', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::init', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'At the start of a run (Sort Integers by The Power Value), what strategy is established?', 'Sort Integers by The Power Value: list every integer in [, ], then sort them by Collatz power (the number of steps to reach 1, halving evens and doing 3n+1 on odds), breaking ties by the smaller value. The answer is the k-th element (k=).', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::key-step', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'On the "SHIFT" step ( > ), what happens?', ' has key (power , value ) which outranks the key (power , value ), so shift  one slot right to make room.', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::state', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'What does the `values` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `values` in sync: the integers, in current (partially sorted) order', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::complexity', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Sort Integers by The Power Value"?', 'O(n·log n·C). O(n). Compute Collatz power for each number with memoization (recursive); Sort `[lo..hi]` by `(power, value)`, return k-th element', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value::outcome', 'prep-sorting-sort-integers-by-the-power-value', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Fully sorted by (power, value). The k-th element (index ) is  — that is the answer.', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::pattern', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'Which approach fits "The Number of Weak Characters in the Game"?', 'Sort by attack **descending**, ties by defense **ascending**', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::init', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'At the start of a run (The Number of Weak Characters in the Game), what strategy is established?', 'Weak Characters: a character is weak if some OTHER character has strictly greater attack AND strictly greater defense. We sort by attack descending (ties by defense ascending), then sweep once tracking the largest defense seen so far.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::key-step', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'On the "SWAP" step (<->), what happens?', 'Swap the winner into slot . Now positions 0… are locked in attack-descending order.', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::state', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'What does the `props` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `props` in sync: current ordering (bars show attack, label shows defense)', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::complexity', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'What are the time and space complexities for "The Number of Weak Characters in the Game"?', 'O(n log n). O(1). Sort by attack **descending**, ties by defense **ascending**; Sweep left-to-right tracking `maxDef`; if `defense < maxDef`, it''s weak', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game::outcome', 'prep-sorting-the-number-of-weak-characters-in-the-game', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Sweep complete.  character weak. Time O(n log n) for the sort, Space O(1) extra.', 5),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::pattern', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'Which approach fits "Top K Frequent Elements"?', 'Count frequencies with a map, then use **bucket sort**: `buckets[freq]` holds elements with that frequency', 0),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::init', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'At the start of a run (Top K Frequent Elements), what strategy is established?', 'Top K Frequent Elements: return the  value that appear most often in the array. We count frequencies in O(n), then bucket-sort by count so we never need to sort the values themselves.', 1),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::key-step', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'On the "BUCKETS" step (0..), what happens?', 'Bucket sort: place each element into buckets[freq], where the index is its frequency. There are at most n+1 =  buckets, so this is O(n) — no comparison sort needed.', 2),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::state', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'What does the `nums` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `nums` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::complexity', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Top K Frequent Elements"?', 'O(n). O(n). Count frequencies with a map, then use **bucket sort**: `buckets[freq]` holds elements with that frequency; Iterate buckets from highest to lowest, collect unti', 4),
  ('prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements::outcome', 'prep-sorting-top-k-frequent-elements', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Walked every bucket. Fewer than k distinct values existed, so the answer is everything collected: [].', 5),
  ('prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator::pattern', 'prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator', 'Which approach fits "Basic Calculator"?', 'Track running `res` and `sign` (+1 or -1)', 0),
  ('prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator::init', 'prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator', 'At the start of a run (Basic Calculator), what strategy is established?', 'Basic Calculator: evaluate "" with +, −, parentheses and spaces. Keep a running res and a sign (+1 or −1). On ''('' we push res and sign onto a stack and reset; on '')'' we fold the inner result back into the saved outer state.', 1),
  ('prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator::key-step', 'prep-stacks-queues-basic-calculator', 'On the "SIGN" step (sign = −1), what happens?', 'Saw ''−'', so the next number is subtracted: set sign = −1. res stays .', 2),
