  ('prep-strings-group-shifted-strings::complexity', 'prep-strings-group-shifted-strings', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Group Shifted Strings"?', 'O(n·L). O(n·L). Group Shifted Strings', 4),
  ('prep-strings-group-shifted-strings::outcome', 'prep-strings-group-shifted-strings', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every word placed. There are  distinct shift groups — that is the answer.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::pattern', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'Which approach fits "Is anagram"?', 'Same letter tally; ++ for s, -- for t cancels to zero', 0),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::init', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'At the start of a run (Is anagram), what strategy is established?', 'Is Anagram: two strings are anagrams if they use exactly the same letters the same number of times. We keep one shared tally: ++ for every letter of s and -- for every letter of t. If every count cancels to zero, they match.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::key-step', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'On the "TALLY" step (+ −), what happens?', 'Index : add s[]='''' (++) and subtract t[]='''' (−−). The tally now reads  for '''' and  for ''''.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::state', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index scanned in both strings', 3),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::complexity', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is anagram"?', 'O(n). O(1). len match; ++s[i] --t[i]; all counts zero', 4),
  ('prep-strings-is-anagram::outcome', 'prep-strings-is-anagram', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Zero-check: letter '''' cancelled to 0 — s and t use it equally often. Keep checking the remaining letters.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::pattern', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'Which approach fits "Is isomorphic"?', 'Two-way letter mapping s<->t must never contradict', 0),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::init', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'At the start of a run (Is isomorphic), what strategy is established?', 'Is Isomorphic: two strings are isomorphic when characters in s can be replaced to get t with a consistent one-to-one mapping. Walk both strings in lockstep, enforcing s[i]→t[i] and t[i]→s[i] at every position.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::key-step', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'On the "CONFLICT" step (← ≠ ), what happens?', 'Conflict: '''' is already mapped back from '''', but here '''' also maps to ''''. Two different characters cannot map onto the same one. Not isomorphic.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::state', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'What does the `s` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `s` in sync: characters of s', 3),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::complexity', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is isomorphic"?', 'O(n). O(1). m1[a]==b and m2[b]==a else conflict', 4),
  ('prep-strings-is-isomorphic::outcome', 'prep-strings-is-isomorphic', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Consistent — record ''''→'''' in the s→t table and ''''→'''' in the t→s table. Continue to the next index.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::pattern', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'Which approach fits "Is palindrome"?', 'l and r march inward, skipping junk, comparing lowercased', 0),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::init', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'At the start of a run (Is palindrome), what strategy is established?', 'Is Palindrome: does the string read the same forwards and backwards, ignoring case and any non-alphanumeric characters? Two pointers l=0 and r= march inward, skipping junk and comparing lowercased characters.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::key-step', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'On the "MISMATCH" step ('''' ≠ ''''), what happens?', 'Compare lowercased characters: ''''→'''' at index  versus ''''→'''' at index . They differ, so the string is NOT a palindrome — return false.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::state', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: the string split into a per-cell char array', 3),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::complexity', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Is palindrome"?', 'O(n). O(1). skip non-alnum both ends; toLower compare; l++ r--', 4),
  ('prep-strings-is-palindrome::outcome', 'prep-strings-is-palindrome', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Compare lowercased characters: ''''→'''' at index  versus ''''→'''' at index . They match, so move both pointers inward: l++ → , r-- → .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::pattern', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'Which approach fits "Longest common prefix"?', 'Compare column by column across all words', 0),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::init', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'At the start of a run (Longest common prefix), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Common Prefix by vertical scan: fix word 0 ("") as the yardstick and walk its characters column by column. At each column, every other word must have the same character; the first mismatch (or a word that runs out) ends the prefix.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::key-step', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'On the "MISMATCH" step ('''' ≠ ''''), what happens?', 'Word  ("") has '''' at index , which differs from ''''. That breaks the prefix here. Answer = word0[:] = "".', 2),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::state', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'What does the `col` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `col` in sync: char column currently being compared', 3),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::complexity', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest common prefix"?', 'O(n*m). O(1). for i in word0: any mismatch/short -> return word0[:i]', 4),
  ('prep-strings-longest-common-prefix::outcome', 'prep-strings-longest-common-prefix', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'We consumed all of word 0 without any mismatch, so word 0 itself is a prefix of every word. The longest common prefix is "".', 5),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::pattern', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'Which approach fits "Longest Happy String"?', 'See Longest Happy String pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::init', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'At the start of a run (Longest Happy String), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Happy String: build the longest string using a= ''a'', b= ''b'', c= ''c'' with no three of the same letter in a row. Greedily, each round we try the letter with the most remaining.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::key-step', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'On the "PICK" step (+), what happens?', 'Append '''' (the letter with the most remaining that is still legal here). It now has  left. String so far: "".', 2),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::state', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'What does the `res` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `res` in sync: characters chosen so far, in order', 3),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::complexity', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest Happy String"?', 'O(a+b+c). O(1). Longest Happy String', 4),
  ('prep-strings-longest-happy-string::outcome', 'prep-strings-longest-happy-string', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'No letter can be appended — either everything is used up, or the only letters left would form three in a row. The happy string is "" (length ).', 5),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::pattern', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'Which approach fits "Longest palindromic substring"?', 'Every index is a mirror center; grow outward while chars match', 0),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::init', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'At the start of a run (Longest palindromic substring), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Palindromic Substring by expand-from-center: every index is a possible mirror center. For each center we grow a window outward while the two edge characters match, then keep the longest span seen. Time O(n^2), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::key-step', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'On the "STOP" step (edge), what happens?', 'A pointer ran off the end (l=, r=), so the window can''t grow further. The palindrome found is "" (length ).', 2),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::state', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'What does the `l` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `l` in sync: left edge of the current expansion', 3),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::complexity', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest palindromic substring"?', 'O(n^2). O(1). expand(i,i) and expand(i,i+1); keep longest span', 4),
  ('prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring::outcome', 'prep-strings-longest-palindromic-substring', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All  centers have been expanded. The longest palindromic substring is "" (length ), starting at index .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::pattern', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'Which approach fits "Longest substring with unique"?', 'Window jumps its left edge past the last duplicate', 0),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::init', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'At the start of a run (Longest substring with unique), what strategy is established?', 'Longest substring with all-unique characters. Slide a window over "" with left edge l and right edge r, remembering the last index each character appeared at. Whenever the incoming character was already inside the window, jump l past that old copy so the window stays duplicate-free.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::key-step', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'On the "READ" step (read ''''), what happens?', 'Read '''' at index . It is not present in the current window [..], so the window is still all-unique — no need to move l.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::state', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'What does the `l` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `l` in sync: left edge of the current window', 3),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::complexity', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest substring with unique"?', 'O(n). O(1). last[c]>=l -> l=last[c]+1; track r-l+1', 4),
  ('prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique::outcome', 'prep-strings-longest-substring-with-unique', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Scanned the whole string. The longest window that stayed all-unique had length .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::pattern', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'Which approach fits "Min insertions to form palin-"?', 'Answer is n minus the longest palindromic subsequence', 0),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::init', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'At the start of a run (Min insertions to form palin-), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum insertions to make "" a palindrome. The trick: the fewest insertions equals n − LPS, where LPS is the Longest Palindromic Subsequence. We build LPS with an interval DP where dp[l][r] is the LPS length of the substring s[l..r].', 1),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::key-step', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'On the "SKIP" step (dp[][]=), what happens?', 's[]='''' differs from s[]='''', so drop one end and keep the better subsequence. dp[][] = max(dp[][]=, dp[][]=) = .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::state', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: the input split into characters', 3),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::complexity', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Min insertions to form palin-"?', 'O(n^2). O(n^2). LPS interval DP; match -> +2 inside, else max(drop end); n-dp[0][n-1]', 4),
  ('prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin::outcome', 'prep-strings-min-insertions-to-form-palin', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The whole-string cell dp[0][] =  is the longest palindromic subsequence length. Every character NOT in it needs a mirror inserted, so the answer is n − LPS =  −  = .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::pattern', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'Which approach fits "Min window substring"?', 'Grow right until t is covered, then shrink left to smallest', 0),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::init', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'At the start of a run (Min window substring), what strategy is established?', 'Min Window Substring: find the shortest slice of s that contains every character of t (with multiplicity). We slide a window over s, growing the right edge to cover t, then shrinking the left edge to make it as small as possible. required =  distinct char(s).', 1),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::key-step', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'On the "RECORD" step (best=""), what happens?', 'The window s[..] = "" covers all of t and is shorter than any before (length ). Record it as the new best.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::state', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'What does the `s` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `s` in sync: the search string, one char per cell', 3),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::complexity', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Min window substring"?', 'O(n). O(1). need map; formed==required -> shrink l, record best', 4),
  ('prep-strings-min-window-substring::outcome', 'prep-strings-min-window-substring', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The window s[..] = "" covers all of t and is shorter than any before (length ). Record it as the new best.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::pattern', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Add to Make Parentheses Valid"?', 'See Minimum Add To Make Parentheses Valid pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::init', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Add to Make Parentheses Valid), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum Add to Make Parentheses Valid: scan left to right with two counters. open = unmatched ''('' still waiting for a '')''; close = orphan '')'' that has no ''('' to its left. The answer is open + close. Time O(n), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::key-step', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'On the "MATCH" step (open=), what happens?', 'Char  is '')'' and there is a waiting ''('' (open was ). They pair up, so decrement open to . No insertion needed.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::state', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current index being scanned', 3),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::complexity', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Add to Make Parentheses Valid"?', 'O(n). O(1). Minimum Add To Make Parentheses Valid', 4),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid::outcome', 'prep-strings-minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Scan finished.  ''('' are still unmatched (each needs a '')'') and  '')'' were orphans (each needed a ''(''). Minimum insertions = open + close =  +  = .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::pattern', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Remove to Make Valid Parentheses"?', 'See Minimum Remove To Make Valid Parentheses pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::init', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Remove to Make Valid Parentheses), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum Remove to Make Valid Parentheses: delete the fewest brackets so every "(" has a matching ")". Scan left to right, pushing the index of each unmatched "(" onto a stack; a ")" cancels the newest one, and anything that never matches gets removed.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::key-step', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'On the "DROP" step (remove ), what happens?', 'Char  is ")" but the stack is empty — there is no open bracket to match it. Mark index  for removal (shown as *).', 2),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::state', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: current buffer, chars marked for removal show as ''*''', 3),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::complexity', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Remove to Make Valid Parentheses"?', 'O(n). O(n). Minimum Remove To Make Valid Parentheses', 4),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses::outcome', 'prep-strings-minimum-remove-to-make-valid-parentheses', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Strip every char marked "*". The remaining string "" is valid and we removed the minimum number of brackets ().', 5),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::pattern', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Time Difference"?', 'See Minimum Time Difference pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::init', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Time Difference), what strategy is established?', 'Minimum Time Difference: find the smallest gap (in minutes) between any two clock times on a 24h circle. First convert each "HH:MM" to minutes since midnight.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::key-step', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'On the "FILL" step (m ✓), what happens?', 'Adjacent gap  →  =  −  =  min. That beats the previous best, so the new minimum is  min.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::state', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'What does the `timePoints` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `timePoints` in sync: original, unsorted labels for reference', 3),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::complexity', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Time Difference"?', 'O(n log n). O(n). Minimum Time Difference', 4),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-difference::outcome', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-difference', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All adjacent gaps and the wrap-around are checked. The minimum time difference is  minute.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::pattern', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'Which approach fits "Minimum Time to Make Rope Colorful"?', 'See Minimum Time To Make Rope Colorful pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::init', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'At the start of a run (Minimum Time to Make Rope Colorful), what strategy is established?', 'Make Rope Colorful: remove balloons so no two adjacent share a colour, at minimum total removal time. Greedily scan left to right — within each run of equal colours we must keep exactly one balloon, so we keep the costliest and pay for the rest.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::key-step', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'On the "CLOSE" step (+ cost=), what happens?', 'Balloon  is colour '''', different from ''''. The previous group closes: keep the costliest (max=) and remove the rest, paying sum − max =  −  = . Running answer = .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::state', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'What does the `colors` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `colors` in sync: the balloon colours, one char per cell', 3),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::complexity', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Minimum Time to Make Rope Colorful"?', 'O(n). O(1). Minimum Time To Make Rope Colorful', 4),
  ('prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful::outcome', 'prep-strings-minimum-time-to-make-rope-colorful', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The array ends, so close the final group: pay sum − max =  −  = . Total minimum time = .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::pattern', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'Which approach fits "Number of Matching Subsequences"?', 'See Number Of Matching Subsequences pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::init', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'At the start of a run (Number of Matching Subsequences), what strategy is established?', 'Number of Matching Subsequences: count how many of the  words are subsequences of "". Each word waits in the bucket of the next character it needs; every word starts in the bucket of its first letter.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::key-step', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'On the "MATCH" step (""), what happens?', '"" consumed its last character '''' — it is a full subsequence of "". Count it. Total so far: .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::state', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'What does the `s` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `s` in sync: the source string, one char per array cell', 3),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::complexity', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Number of Matching Subsequences"?', 'O(. O(words). Number Of Matching Subsequences', 4),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences::outcome', 'prep-strings-number-of-matching-subsequences', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Finished scanning "".  of  word(s) were subsequences${
      matched.length ? ', 5),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::pattern', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'Which approach fits "Number of Steps to Reduce a Number in Binary to One"?', 'See Number Of Steps To Reduce A Number In Binary Representation To One pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::init', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'At the start of a run (Number of Steps to Reduce a Number in Binary to One), what strategy is established?', 'Reduce the binary number  to 1. Rule: if the number is even, halve it (drop the last bit — 1 step); if odd, add 1 (2 steps to also halve). We simulate this bit-by-bit from the right, carrying a +1 when needed. Time O(n), Space O(1).', 1),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::key-step', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'On the "EVEN" step (+1), what happens?', 'Bit at index  is ; with incoming carry  the value is , which is even. Just halve it — 1 step. No carry produced.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::state', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: current bit being processed (right-to-left, stops before index 0)', 3),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::complexity', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Number of Steps to Reduce a Number in Binary to One"?', 'O(n). O(1). Number Of Steps To Reduce A Number In Binary Representation To One', 4),
  ('prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-::outcome', 'prep-strings-number-of-steps-to-reduce-a-number-in-binary-representation-', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Reached the leading bit (index 0). Any leftover carry () is one final +1 step to turn the top bits into a single 1. Total steps = .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::pattern', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'Which approach fits "Ransom note"?', 'Spend magazine letters to build the note', 0),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::init', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'At the start of a run (Ransom note), what strategy is established?', 'Ransom Note: can we spell "" using only the letters in the magazine "", each magazine letter used at most once? Count every magazine letter, then spend one per note letter.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::key-step', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'On the "FAIL" step (no ''''), what happens?', 'The pool has zero '''' left, so the note cannot be spelled. Return false.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::state', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'What does the `note` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `note` in sync: ransom note chars we must spell', 3),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::complexity', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Ransom note"?', 'O(n). O(1). count magazine; for each note char: 0 -> false else --', 4),
  ('prep-strings-ransom-note::outcome', 'prep-strings-ransom-note', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Spend one '''' from the pool: its count drops  → . Move to the next note letter.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::pattern', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'Which approach fits "Reverse words"?', 'Reverse the whole string, then reverse each word back', 0),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::init', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'At the start of a run (Reverse words), what strategy is established?', 'Reverse Words: reverse the order of the words in "" while keeping each word''s letters intact. Trick: reverse the whole string, then reverse every word back — all in place, O(1) extra space.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::key-step', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'On the "WORD" step (span [..]), what happens?', 'The span [..] is a single character (or empty), so there is nothing to flip — it already reads correctly.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::state', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: current byte array (post-trim shrink applied)', 3),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::complexity', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Reverse words"?', 'O(n). O(1). trim; rev(all); rev(each word span)', 4),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words::outcome', 'prep-strings-reverse-words', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every word span has been flipped back, so the answer is "" — the words in reverse order with their letters intact.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::pattern', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'Which approach fits "Reverse Words in a String"?', 'See Reverse Words In A String pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::init', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'At the start of a run (Reverse Words in a String), what strategy is established?', 'Reverse Words in a String: we want the words in reverse order, collapsing any extra spaces. The plan is Split + Reverse — first cut the string into words, then reverse the list of words with two pointers.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::key-step', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'On the "COMPARE" step (swap  & ), what happens?', 'l =  points at "" and r =  points at "". Since l < r, exchange these two words so the ends move toward the middle.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::state', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'What does the `words` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `words` in sync: current order of the extracted words', 3),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::complexity', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Reverse Words in a String"?', 'O(n). O(n). Reverse Words In A String', 4),
  ('prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string::outcome', 'prep-strings-reverse-words-in-a-string', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The pointers crossed, so the list is fully reversed. Join the words with single spaces to get the answer: "".', 5),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::pattern', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'Which approach fits "Rotate string"?', 'goal is a window hiding inside s+s', 0),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::init', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'At the start of a run (Rotate string), what strategy is established?', 'Rotate String: goal is a rotation of s iff both have equal length AND goal appears somewhere inside s + s. Every rotation of s is a length- window hiding in the doubled string.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::key-step', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'On the "WINDOW" step (start=), what happens?', 'Try the window starting at index : double[..] = "". Compare it to goal character by character.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::state', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'What does the `double` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `double` in sync: s + s, split into chars — the track we slide the window along', 3),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::complexity', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Rotate string"?', 'O(n). O(n). len equal AND goal is substring of s+s', 4),
  ('prep-strings-rotate-string::outcome', 'prep-strings-rotate-string', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The whole window double[..] equals "". goal is a rotation of s — return true.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::pattern', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'Which approach fits "Run length encoding"?', 'Squash each equal run into char+count', 0),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::init', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'At the start of a run (Run length encoding), what strategy is established?', 'Run-length encoding squashes each maximal run of equal characters into character+count. Seed the first run: character '''' with run = 1, starting at index 0.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::key-step', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'On the "RESET" step (c='''' run=1), what happens?', 'Begin a new run: character '''' with run = 1, starting at index .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::state', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: input split into characters', 3),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::complexity', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Run length encoding"?', 'O(n). O(n). same -> run++; else flush char,run and reset', 4),
  ('prep-strings-run-length-encoding::outcome', 'prep-strings-run-length-encoding', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The scan is over, but the last run '''' has not been written yet. Flush it now. Encoded result: "".', 5),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::pattern', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'Which approach fits "Shortest subarray contains all"?', 'Grow right, shrink left while the running sum still reaches target', 0),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::init', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'At the start of a run (Shortest subarray contains all), what strategy is established?', 'Shortest subarray reaching a target sum. Slide a window: grow the right edge to add elements, and shrink from the left while the window sum still reaches , recording the smallest length seen.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::key-step', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'On the "GROW" step (+nums[]=), what happens?', 'Grow the window: add nums[] = . The window is [..] with sum .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::state', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'What does the `l` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `l` in sync: left edge of the window', 3),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::complexity', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Shortest subarray contains all"?', 'O(n). O(n). sum>=target -> record r-l+1, sum-=nums[l], l++', 4),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all::outcome', 'prep-strings-shortest-subarray-contains-all', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Grow the window: add nums[] = . The window is [..] with sum .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::pattern', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'Which approach fits "Shortest Way to Form String"?', 'See Shortest Way To Form String pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::init', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'At the start of a run (Shortest Way to Form String), what strategy is established?', 'Shortest Way to Form String: build target "" by concatenating subsequences of source "". Greedily sweep source left-to-right, matching as many target chars as possible per pass; each full sweep costs one subsequence.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::key-step', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'On the "SKIP" step (source[]=''''), what happens?', 'source[] = '''' does not equal target[] = ''''. Skip this source character and keep scanning; j stays at .', 2),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::state', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: pointer scanning source', 3),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::complexity', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Shortest Way to Form String"?', 'O(. O(1). Shortest Way To Form String', 4),
  ('prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string::outcome', 'prep-strings-shortest-way-to-form-string', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'target "" is fully formed using  subsequence of source. Answer = .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::pattern', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'Which approach fits "Strings Differ by One Character"?', 'See Strings Differ By One Character pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::init', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'At the start of a run (Strings Differ by One Character), what strategy is established?', 'Strings Differ by One Character: is there a pair of words that match everywhere except at exactly one position? For each column we blank that column with "*"; two words sharing the same blanked key differ only at that column.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::key-step', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'On the "FOUND" step (), what happens?', 'Word  ("") makes key "", which word  ("") already produced this column. They agree everywhere except column , so they differ by exactly one character. Answer: true.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::state', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'What does the `L` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `L` in sync: shared word length', 3),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::complexity', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Strings Differ by One Character"?', 'O(n·L). O(n·L). Strings Differ By One Character', 4),
  ('prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character::outcome', 'prep-strings-strings-differ-by-one-character', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Word  ("") blanks column  to key "". It is new for this column, so remember it and continue.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::pattern', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'Which approach fits "Sum of Prefix Scores of Strings"?', 'See Sum Of Prefix Scores Of Strings pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::init', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'At the start of a run (Sum of Prefix Scores of Strings), what strategy is established?', 'Sum of Prefix Scores: the score of a word is the number of (word, prefix) pairs whose prefix equals a prefix of that word — i.e. how many words share each of its prefixes, summed over all its prefixes. We insert every word into a trie, counting how many words pass through each node, then re-walk each word adding those counts.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::key-step', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'On the "SCORE" step (score ""), what happens?', 'Now score "". Re-walk it from the root and add up the counter at each prefix node — that sum is the word''s prefix score.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::state', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'What does the `wi` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `wi` in sync: current word index', 3),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::complexity', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Sum of Prefix Scores of Strings"?', 'O(n·L). O(n·L). Sum Of Prefix Scores Of Strings', 4),
  ('prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings::outcome', 'prep-strings-sum-of-prefix-scores-of-strings', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All words scored. The prefix scores are [], which sum to .', 5),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::pattern', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'Which approach fits "Swap Adjacent in LR String"?', 'See Swap Adjacent In Lr String pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::init', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'At the start of a run (Swap Adjacent in LR String), what strategy is established?', 'Swap Adjacent in LR String: an ''L'' can only move left and an ''R'' can only move right (past ''X'' blanks). Walk both strings with two pointers, skipping ''X'', and check the non-X letters match in order with the right position constraint.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::key-step', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'On the "COMPARE" step ( vs ), what happens?', 'Compare the next real letters: start[] = '''' and target[] = ''''. They must be the same letter.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::state', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'What does the `start` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `start` in sync: start string as-is', 3),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::complexity', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Swap Adjacent in LR String"?', 'O(n). O(1). Swap Adjacent In Lr String', 4),
  ('prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string::outcome', 'prep-strings-swap-adjacent-in-lr-string', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', ''''' at start[] can reach target[]: ${a === ''L'' ? ', 5),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::pattern', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'Which approach fits "Swap even odd"?', 'Swap neighbors two at a time', 0),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::init', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'At the start of a run (Swap even odd), what strategy is established?', 'Swap Even Odd: walk the string two characters at a time and swap each adjacent pair (index i with i+1). We step i += 2 so every neighbouring couple is swapped exactly once.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::key-step', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'On the "SWAP" step (), what happens?', 'Swap them: index  and  become '''' and ''''. Now advance i += 2 to the next pair.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::state', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'What does the `chars` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `chars` in sync: working char array (mutated as we swap)', 3),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::complexity', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Swap even odd"?', 'O(n). O(1). i+=2: swap b[i],b[i+1]', 4),
  ('prep-strings-swap-even-odd::outcome', 'prep-strings-swap-even-odd', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Swap them: index  and  become '''' and ''''. Now advance i += 2 to the next pair.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::pattern', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'Which approach fits "Text Justification"?', 'See Text Justification pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::init', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'At the start of a run (Text Justification), what strategy is established?', 'Text Justification: greedily pack as many words as fit into each -wide line, then space them out. Every line except the last is fully justified; the last line is left-justified.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::key-step', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'On the "STOP" step ( words), what happens?', 'No more words fit.  words occupy  chars, leaving  spaces across  gaps →  per gap, with the leftmost  gap getting one extra.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::state', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: first word index of the current line', 3),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::complexity', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Text Justification"?', 'O(n). O(n). Text Justification', 4),
  ('prep-strings-text-justification::outcome', 'prep-strings-text-justification', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'All words placed. The paragraph is  justified line, each exactly  characters wide.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::pattern', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'Which approach fits "Valid Number"?', 'See Valid Number pattern', 0),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::init', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'At the start of a run (Valid Number), what strategy is established?', 'Valid Number: scan "" once, tracking three flags — seenDigit, seenDot, seenExp. Every character must be legal in its position; at the end the string is valid only if at least one digit was seen.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::key-step', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'On the "EXP" step ('''' exp ok), what happens?', ''''' begins the exponent. Set seenExp = true and reset seenDigit = false, because the part after ''e''/''E'' must contain its own digit.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::state', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: char currently under inspection', 3),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::complexity', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Valid Number"?', 'O(n). O(1). Valid Number', 4),
  ('prep-strings-valid-number::outcome', 'prep-strings-valid-number', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', ''''' is not a digit, sign, ''e''/''E'', or ''.'', so it can never appear in a valid number. Reject.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::pattern', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'Which approach fits "Word break"?', 'dp[i] true if some cut j leaves dp[j] reachable and s[j:i] is a word', 0),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::init', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'At the start of a run (Word break), what strategy is established?', 'Word Break: can "" be cut into a sequence of dictionary words? dp[i] means the prefix s[0:i] is fully segmentable. We fill dp left to right in O(n²) time and O(n) space.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::key-step', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'On the "SET" step (dp[]=true), what happens?', 'Match! The prefix s[0:] is segmentable and "" is a word, so "" is segmentable too. Set dp[] = true and stop scanning cuts for i=.', 2),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::state', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'What does the `dp` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `dp` in sync: dp[i] = prefix s[0:i] is fully segmentable; dp has length s.length + 1', 3),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::complexity', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Word break"?', 'O(n^2). O(n). dp[0]=true; dp[i]|=dp[j] && dict[s[j:i]]', 4),
  ('prep-strings-word-break::outcome', 'prep-strings-word-break', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'No cut worked for i=: the prefix "" cannot be split into dictionary words. dp[] stays false.', 5),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::pattern', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'Which approach fits "Word wrap"?', 'DP packs words per line, paying slack^2 for each line', 0),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::init', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'At the start of a run (Word wrap), what strategy is established?', 'Word Wrap: pack these  words into lines no wider than . Each non-last line pays slack² (the leftover space squared). dp[i] = the minimum total cost to wrap words[i..end], solved right-to-left so dp[i+1..] are already known.', 1),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::key-step', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'On the "TRY" step (cost=), what happens?', 'Line = words .. (""), width , slack . Cost = slack² + dp[] = ² +  = . Break after word ?', 2),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::state', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'What does the `i` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `i` in sync: line-start word being solved (outer loop)', 3),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::complexity', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Word wrap"?', 'O(n^2). O(n). dp[i]=min over j of (rem^2 + dp[j+1]); next[i] records the cut', 4),
  ('prep-strings-word-wrap::outcome', 'prep-strings-word-wrap', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Table complete. dp[0] =  is the minimum total slack² cost. Follow next[] from word 0 to read off the wrapped lines shown below.', 5),
  ('prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator', 'Which approach fits "Binary Search Tree Iterator"?', 'Maintain a stack; `pushLeft` pushes a node and all its left children', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator', 'On the "NEXT" step (yield ), what happens?', 'Next(): pop  and emit it — the in-order sequence so far is []. Now open its RIGHT subtree.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator::state', 'prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator', 'What does the `stack` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `stack` in sync: node indices on the controlled stack, bottom→top', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary Search Tree Iterator"?', 'O(1) amortized. O(h). Maintain a stack; `pushLeft` pushes a node and all its left children; `Next()`: pop top, call `pushLeft(top.Right)`, return value', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-search-tree-iterator', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'HasNext() is now false and the stack is empty. The iterator produced the full sorted order [] using only O(h) stack space.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum', 'Which approach fits "Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum"?', 'Post-order DFS: at each node, compute `left` and `right` subtree max gains (floor at 0 to drop negatives)', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum', 'On the "THROUGH" step (through = ), what happens?', 'A path turning at node  is worth  +  +  = , which does not beat the current best of . Leave the global maximum unchanged.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum::state', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node index currently being processed (post-order)', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum"?', 'O(n). O(h). Post-order DFS: at each node, compute `left` and `right` subtree max gains (floor at 0 to drop negatives); Update global max with `node.Val + left + right` (the', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-maximum-path-sum', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every node has been visited in post-order. The largest path sum found anywhere in the tree is .', 4),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view', 'Which approach fits "Binary Tree Right Side View"?', 'DFS: visit **right child first**, then left. First node at each depth is the rightmost.', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view', 'On the "VISIT" step (depth , hidden), what happens?', 'Node  sits at depth , but we already saw a node at that depth (), which was further right.  is hidden behind it — visit but do not record.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view::state', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view', 'What does the `current` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `current` in sync: node index being visited (null on INIT/DONE)', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary Tree Right Side View"?', 'O(n). O(h). DFS: visit **right child first**, then left. First node at each depth is the rightmost.; If `depth == len(res)`, this is the first node seen at this depth → add', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-right-side-view', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'DFS finished. Reading top-to-bottom, the rightmost node at each depth gives the right side view: [].', 4),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively', 'Which approach fits "Binary tree traversal iteratively"?', 'Push the whole left spine, pop to visit, then dive right', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively', 'On the "VISIT" step (visit ), what happens?', 'Left is exhausted, so pop node  and visit it — append  to the output. In-order visits the left subtree, then the node, then the right subtree.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively::state', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively', 'What does the `cur` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cur` in sync: index of the current node (2i+1/2i+2 layout); null = walked off the tree', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary tree traversal iteratively"?', 'O(n). O(h). for cur: push & go left; pop visit; cur=right', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-traversal-iteratively', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Both cur and the stack are empty, so every node is visited. The in-order sequence is [].', 4),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal', 'Which approach fits "Binary Tree Vertical Order Traversal"?', 'BFS with column tracking: root=col 0, left=col-1, right=col+1', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal', 'On the "ENQUEUE" step (→col ), what happens?', 'Node  has a left child . A left child sits one column to the left, so it goes to column . Enqueue it.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal::state', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal', 'What does the `visited` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `visited` in sync: node indices already popped + recorded', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary Tree Vertical Order Traversal"?', 'O(n). O(n). BFS with column tracking: root=col 0, left=col-1, right=col+1; BFS naturally gives top-to-bottom, left-to-right order within same column', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-vertical-order-traversal', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The queue is empty. Reading columns left to right gives the answer: ${result.map((c) => ', 4),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal::pattern', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal', 'Which approach fits "Binary Tree Zigzag Level Order Traversal"?', 'Standard BFS level-by-level. For each level, place values at index `i` (left-to-right) or `levelSize-1-i` (right-to-left', 0),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal::key-step', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal', 'On the "PLACE" step ( → slot ), what happens?', 'Dequeue node  (position  in this level) and place its value at slot  because the level fills .', 1),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal::state', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal', 'What does the `visited` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `visited` in sync: node indices already dequeued and recorded', 2),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal::complexity', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Binary Tree Zigzag Level Order Traversal"?', 'O(n). O(n). Standard BFS level-by-level. For each level, place values at index `i` (left-to-right) or `levelSize-1-i` (right-to-left); Toggle `leftToRight` flag each level', 3),
  ('prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal::outcome', 'prep-trees-binary-tree-zigzag-level-order-traversal', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every level has been processed. The zigzag level order is [].', 4),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list::pattern', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list', 'Which approach fits "Convert Binary Search Tree to Sorted Doubly Linked List"?', 'In-order traversal: at each node, link `last.Right = node` and `node.Left = last`', 0),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list::key-step', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list', 'On the "ADVANCE" step (last = ), what happens?', 'Mark  as the most recent node (last = ). Its right subtree will be linked next.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list::state', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list', 'What does the `status` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `status` in sync: per-node visit status by tree index', 2),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list::complexity', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert Binary Search Tree to Sorted Doubly Linked List"?', 'O(n). O(h). In-order traversal: at each node, link `last.Right = node` and `node.Left = last`; Track `first` (smallest) and `last` (most recent). After traversal, connect `', 3),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list::outcome', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-search-tree-to-sorted-doubly-linked-list', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Traversal done. Close the circle: first.Left = last (.Left = ) and last.Right = first (.Right = ). Return first () as the head.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly::pattern', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly', 'Which approach fits "Convert binary tree to doubly"?', 'Inorder walk; link prev<->cur as each node is visited', 0),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly::key-step', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly', 'On the "LINK" step (↔), what happens?', 'Link  and : set prev.Next =  and .Prev = . This appends  to the tail of the list.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly::state', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly', 'What does the `status` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `status` in sync: per level-order index', 2),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly::complexity', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert binary tree to doubly"?', 'O(n). O(h). dfs left; link prev,cur; prev=cur; dfs right', 3),
  ('prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly::outcome', 'prep-trees-convert-binary-tree-to-doubly', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Inorder walk complete. The nodes are now a sorted doubly-linked list: . The head is . Time O(n), space O(h) for the recursion stack.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::pattern', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'Which approach fits "Convert sorted array to BST"?', 'Middle element becomes the root; recurse on the two halves', 0),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::init', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'At the start of a run (Convert sorted array to BST), what strategy is established?', 'Convert Sorted Array to BST: the array is already sorted, so the middle element is the root of a balanced BST. build(l, r) takes the mid of [l, r] as a subtree root, then recurses on the left half and the right half.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::key-step', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'On the "MID" step (m=), what happens?', 'In range [, ] the middle index is m = ⌊( + ) / 2⌋ = , so nums[] =  becomes the root of this subtree. Values left of  are smaller, values right are larger.', 2),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::state', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'What does the `l` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `l` in sync: current sub-array left bound', 3),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::complexity', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert sorted array to BST"?', 'O(n). O(n). build(l,r): m=(l+r)/2 root, build(l,m-1), build(m+1,r)', 4),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst::outcome', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-array-to-bst', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Place  as this subtree''s root. Now recurse left on [, ] then right on [, ].', 5),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::pattern', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'Which approach fits "Convert sorted linked list to BST"?', 'Build in inorder, consuming the list head left-to-right', 0),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::init', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'At the start of a run (Convert sorted linked list to BST), what strategy is established?', 'Convert an ascending sorted linked list into a height-balanced BST. First count the  nodes, then build the tree by an in-order recursion: for each range pick the middle as a node, build its left subtree first, consume the current list head as this node''s value, then build the right subtree. Because we build in-order and the list is sorted, the head cursor always lines up with the next value to place. Time O(n), Space O(n).', 1),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::key-step', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'On the "ADVANCE" step (cur→), what happens?', 'Advance the head cursor past . It now points at , ready to feed the right subtree.', 2),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::state', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'What does the `list` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `list` in sync: the sorted list values, head → tail', 3),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::complexity', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Convert sorted linked list to BST"?', 'O(n). O(n). build left; take cur as root and advance; build right', 4),
  ('prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst::outcome', 'prep-trees-convert-sorted-linked-list-to-bst', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The whole list has been consumed in order and the balanced BST is built. Its in-order traversal is exactly the original sorted list . Return the root .', 5),
  ('prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree::pattern', 'prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree', 'Which approach fits "Count Good Nodes in Binary Tree"?', 'DFS passing `maxVal` seen so far on the path from root', 0),
  ('prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree::key-step', 'prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree', 'On the "SKIP" step ( < ), what happens?', 'Visit node . maxVal on this path is , and  < , so an ancestor is larger — node  is NOT good. Carry maxVal =  unchanged into its children.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree::state', 'prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree', 'What does the `current` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `current` in sync: node index being visited', 2),
  ('prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree::complexity', 'prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Count Good Nodes in Binary Tree"?', 'O(n). O(h). DFS passing `maxVal` seen so far on the path from root; If `node.Val >= maxVal`, it''s good; update `maxVal`', 3),
  ('prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree::outcome', 'prep-trees-count-good-nodes-in-binary-tree', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'DFS is complete. Every path was checked against its running maximum, giving  good node in the tree. Time O(n) — one visit per node; Space O(h) — the recursion stack is as deep as the tree.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes::pattern', 'prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes', 'Which approach fits "Find distance of two nodes"?', 'Distance = depth(p)+depth(q) measured down from their LCA', 0),
  ('prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes::key-step', 'prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes', 'On the "LCA" step (pass up ), what happens?', 'Only one side found a target under node , so we pass that candidate () up unchanged.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes::state', 'prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node currently under inspection (ring)', 2),
  ('prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes::complexity', 'prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find distance of two nodes"?', 'O(n). O(h). find LCA; sum depth from lca to each node', 3),
  ('prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes::outcome', 'prep-trees-find-distance-of-two-nodes', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Distance = depth(LCA→) + depth(LCA→) =  +  = . That is the number of edges on the path between the two nodes.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::pattern', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'Which approach fits "Find distance of two nodes"?', 'Distance = depth(a) + depth(b) measured down from their LCA', 0),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::init', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'At the start of a run (Find distance of two nodes), what strategy is established?', 'Distance of two nodes in an n-ary tree. Plan: find the lowest common ancestor (LCA) of  and , then add the two downward level distances from the LCA. Answer = levelDistance(lca, a) + levelDistance(lca, b). Time O(n), Space O(h).', 1),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::key-step', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'On the "LEVEL_ZERO" step ( is the LCA), what happens?', 'Measuring from the LCA  down to : it is the LCA itself, so the level distance is 0.', 2),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::state', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'What does the `nodes` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `nodes` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::complexity', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find distance of two nodes"?', 'O(n). O(h). find LCA; levelDistance(lca,a) + levelDistance(lca,b)', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes::outcome', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-distance-of-two-nodes', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Combine the two downward distances: levelDistance(, ) =  and levelDistance(, ) = . The distance between  and  is  +  = .', 5),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::pattern', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'Which approach fits "Find Kth largest in BST"?', 'Right-node-left visit lists values descending; stop at the kth', 0),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::init', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'At the start of a run (Find Kth largest in BST), what strategy is established?', 'Find the  largest value in the BST. A reverse in-order walk (right → node → left) visits values in descending order, so the  node we touch is the answer. Time O(h+k), Space O(h).', 1),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::key-step', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'On the "VISIT" step ( is #), what happens?', 'Count node : this is the  largest value visited, so k has reached 0. The answer is .', 2),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::state', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'What does the `k` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `k` in sync: the original k (for display)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::complexity', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find Kth largest in BST"?', 'O(h+k). O(h). dfs right; k--; k==0 -> ans; dfs left', 4),
  ('prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst::outcome', 'prep-trees-find-kth-largest-in-bst', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Count node  — that is the  largest so far. k drops to , so keep going: now recurse into the LEFT subtree (smaller values).', 5),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::pattern', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'Which approach fits "Find Leaves of Binary Tree"?', 'A node''s "height" (distance to farthest leaf) determines which group it belongs to', 0),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::init', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'At the start of a run (Find Leaves of Binary Tree), what strategy is established?', 'Find Leaves groups every node by its height — the distance to its farthest leaf. Leaves have height 0, their parents height 1, and so on. A post-order DFS computes each height from the children, then drops the node into layer[height].', 1),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::key-step', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'On the "PLACE" step (h=), what happens?', 'Node : left height , right height , so its height is max(, ) + 1 = . It joins layer , which now reads [].', 2),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::state', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node index currently being processed', 3),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::complexity', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find Leaves of Binary Tree"?', 'O(n). O(n). A node''s "height" (distance to farthest leaf) determines which group it belongs to; Leaves have height 0, their parents height 1, etc.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree::outcome', 'prep-trees-find-leaves-of-binary-tree', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every node is placed. The result peels the tree leaf-layer by leaf-layer: ${layers
      .map((l, idx) => ', 5),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::pattern', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'Which approach fits "Find lowest common ancestor"?', 'The node where two different children each return a hit is the LCA', 0),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::init', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'At the start of a run (Find lowest common ancestor), what strategy is established?', 'Lowest Common Ancestor of  and : recurse post-order. Each node reports whether it (or its subtree) contained a target. The deepest node where two different children each report a hit is the LCA.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::key-step', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'On the "MISS" step (child of  empty), what happens?', 'That child subtree of node  held neither target — nothing to propagate. Keep the hit count at .', 2),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::state', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node index currently being visited', 3),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::complexity', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Find lowest common ancestor"?', 'O(n). O(h). count child hits; >=2 -> root; ==1 -> propagate found', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor::outcome', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-lowest-common-ancestor', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The recursion settled on node  as the lowest common ancestor of  and .', 5),
  ('prep-trees-flip-tree::pattern', 'prep-trees-flip-tree', 'Which approach fits "Flip tree"?', 'Invert by swapping left and right at every node', 0),
  ('prep-trees-flip-tree::key-step', 'prep-trees-flip-tree', 'On the "SWAP" step (swap under ), what happens?', 'Both subtrees of node  are flipped, so now swap them: its old left subtree moves to the right and its old right subtree moves to the left. Node ''s children are mirrored.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-flip-tree::state', 'prep-trees-flip-tree', 'What does the `tree` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `tree` in sync: current (partially flipped) level-order array', 2),
  ('prep-trees-flip-tree::complexity', 'prep-trees-flip-tree', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Flip tree"?', 'O(n). O(h). Left,Right = flip(Right),flip(Left)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-flip-tree::outcome', 'prep-trees-flip-tree', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Node  is a leaf — flip(nil), flip(nil) do nothing and there is nothing to swap. Return it unchanged.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-get-diameter::pattern', 'prep-trees-get-diameter', 'Which approach fits "Get diameter"?', 'Longest path bends through a node = leftHeight + rightHeight', 0),
  ('prep-trees-get-diameter::key-step', 'prep-trees-get-diameter', 'On the "RETURN" step (h=), what happens?', 'Node  returns its own height to its parent: 1 + max(L, R) = 1 + max(, ) = . This is how tall the subtree rooted at  is.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-get-diameter::state', 'prep-trees-get-diameter', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node currently being processed (ring)', 2),
  ('prep-trees-get-diameter::complexity', 'prep-trees-get-diameter', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Get diameter"?', 'O(n). O(h). height dfs; best=max(best,L+R); return 1+max(L,R)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-get-diameter::outcome', 'prep-trees-get-diameter', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every node has been processed. The diameter is the largest L + R found:  edge${
      bestNode !== null ? ', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::pattern', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'Which approach fits "Get diameter"?', 'Through a node = its two tallest child heights + 2; also check child diameters', 0),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::init', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'At the start of a run (Get diameter), what strategy is established?', 'N-ary tree diameter: the longest path between any two nodes. At each node the candidate is its two tallest child heights + 2; we also carry up each child''s own diameter and keep the global max. Time O(n), Space O(h).', 1),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::key-step', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'On the "HEIGHT" step (h()=), what happens?', 'Child  has height . Track the two tallest child heights so far: top1=${max2 >= 0 ? ', 2),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::state', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node currently being processed (team-1 ring)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::complexity', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Get diameter"?', 'O(n). O(h). top1 + top2 + 2, compared against max child diameter', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter::outcome', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-diameter', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every node has been resolved. The overall diameter of the tree is  edges.', 5),
  ('prep-trees-get-height::pattern', 'prep-trees-get-height', 'Which approach fits "Get height"?', 'Height is 1 plus the taller child', 0),
  ('prep-trees-get-height::key-step', 'prep-trees-get-height', 'On the "RIGHT" step (R()=), what happens?', 'Right subtree of node  has height . Node  is 1 plus the taller child.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-get-height::state', 'prep-trees-get-height', 'What does the `current` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `current` in sync: node index we are looking at right now', 2),
  ('prep-trees-get-height::complexity', 'prep-trees-get-height', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Get height"?', 'O(n). O(h). nil->0; return 1+max(L,R)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-get-height::outcome', 'prep-trees-get-height', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every subtree has been measured. The root returns , so the tree''s height is . Time O(n) — each node is visited once; Space O(h) for the recursion stack.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::pattern', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'Which approach fits "Get height"?', 'Height = 1 + the tallest child subtree', 0),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::init', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'At the start of a run (Get height), what strategy is established?', 'Get the height of this -node N-ary tree. Rule: nil → 0, otherwise a node''s height is 1 + the maximum height among its children. We compute it with a post-order DFS from the root.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::key-step', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'On the "UPDATE" step (best=), what happens?', 'Child  returned height , which beats the previous best () for node . Update this node''s tallest-child height to .', 2),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::state', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'What does the `active` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `active` in sync: node currently being processed', 3),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::complexity', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Get height"?', 'O(n). O(h). nil -> 0; return 1 + max(getHeight(child))', 4),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-height::outcome', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-height', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'The root returned , so the whole tree''s height is . Time O(n) — every node is visited once; Space O(h) for the recursion stack.', 5),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::pattern', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'Which approach fits "Inorder Successor in BST"?', 'Walk from root: if `p.Val < curr.Val`, `curr` is a candidate → go left. Otherwise go right.', 0),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::init', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'At the start of a run (Inorder Successor in BST), what strategy is established?', 'Inorder Successor in BST: find the node with the smallest value strictly greater than . We never touch p''s own subtree — we just walk down from the root using the BST order. Whenever p < cur we could still improve, so we record cur as a candidate and go left; otherwise cur is too small, so we go right.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::key-step', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'On the "GO_RIGHT" step (skip ), what happens?', 'p () ≥ cur (), so  is not greater than p and cannot be the successor. Any larger value lies in the right subtree, so move right and keep the current res.', 2),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::state', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'What does the `cur` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `cur` in sync: index of the node we are standing on (null once we fall off)', 3),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::complexity', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Inorder Successor in BST"?', 'O(h). O(1). Walk from root: if `p.Val < curr.Val`, `curr` is a candidate → go left. Otherwise go right.; Last candidate when going left is the answer.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst::outcome', 'prep-trees-inorder-successor-in-bst', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'We walked off the tree. The last candidate we saved is , which is the in-order successor of . (In-order values:  — right after  comes .)', 5),
  ('prep-trees-is-balanced::pattern', 'prep-trees-is-balanced', 'Which approach fits "Is balanced"?', 'Height-return doubles as a flag: -1 means imbalance found', 0),
