  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::pattern', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'Which approach fits "Longest Path With Different Adjacent Characters"?', 'DFS: for each node, track the two longest child contributions where `s[child] != s[node]`', 0),
  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::init', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'At the start of a run (Longest Path With Different Adjacent Characters), what strategy is established?', 'Longest Path With Different Adjacent Characters: find the longest downward path whose adjacent nodes never share the same character. DFS returns the longest single downward chain from each node; the answer is the best "V" path (two chains) through any node.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::key-step', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'On the "BLOCK" step (''''==''''), what happens?', 'Child  shares character '''' with node , so the edge to it is forbidden — its chain contributes nothing here.', 2),
  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::state', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'What does the `parent` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder snapshots `parent` on every emit so each frame shows the algorithm mid-step.', 3),
  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::complexity', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Longest Path With Different Adjacent Characters"?', 'O(n). O(n). DFS: for each node, track the two longest child contributions where `s[child] != s[node]`; Path through node = `max1 + max2 + 1`; return `max1 + 1` upward', 4),
  ('prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters::outcome', 'prep-trees-longest-path-with-different-adjacent-characters', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Every node is resolved. The longest path with all-different adjacent characters has length  node(s).', 5),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree::pattern', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree', 'Which approach fits "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree"?', 'Recursive DFS: if `root == nil || root == p || root == q`, return `root`', 0),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree::key-step', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree', 'On the "SPLIT" step (LCA = ), what happens?', 'Node  received a target from BOTH sides:  came up the left,  came up the right. p and q live in different subtrees here, so node  is their lowest common ancestor.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree::state', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree', 'What does the `current` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `current` in sync: node index currently being visited (pre-order enter)', 2),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree::complexity', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree"?', 'O(n). O(h). Recursive DFS: if `root == nil || root == p || root == q`, return `root`; Recurse left and right. If both return non-nil → root is the LCA', 3),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree::outcome', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'Only the left side returned something (); the right returned nil. Node  passes that non-nil result straight up — both targets (or the single one found so far) are on the left.', 4),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::pattern', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'Which approach fits "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree III"?', 'Same trick as "intersection of two linked lists": two pointers `a` and `b` start at `p` and `q`', 0),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::init', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'At the start of a run (Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree III), what strategy is established?', 'LCA III uses only parent pointers (no root). Same trick as intersecting two linked lists: pointer a starts at p (), pointer b starts at q (). Each walks up to its parent; when one falls off the top it restarts at the other''s start, so both travel the same total distance and meet at the LCA.', 1),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::key-step', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'On the "UP_B" step (b:  → ), what happens?', 'Move pointer b up from  to its parent .', 2),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::state', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'What does the `p` field track in the visualization state?', 'The recorder keeps `p` in sync: start of pointer a', 3),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::complexity', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'What are the time and space complexities for "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree III"?', 'O(h). O(1). Same trick as "intersection of two linked lists": two pointers `a` and `b` start at `p` and `q`; When one reaches `nil`, redirect it to the other''s start', 4),
  ('prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii::outcome', 'prep-trees-lowest-common-ancestor-of-a-binary-tree-iii', 'When the run completes, what does the final step convey?', 'p and q are the same node, so the LCA is that node itself ().', 5),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-monarchy-succession::pattern', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-monarchy-succession', 'Which approach fits "Monarchy succession order"?', 'Parse parent->children lines into a map, then iterative pre-order of names', 0),
  ('prep-trees-nary-tree-monarchy-succession::init', 'prep-trees-nary-tree-monarchy-succession', 'At the start of a run (Monarchy succession order), what strategy is established?', 'Monarchy succession: the parent→children lines are parsed into a family tree rooted at the monarch "". An iterative pre-order walk lists each ruler before their descendants — a stack drives it, pushing successors in reverse so the eldest is popped first.', 1),
